@node "ACCEPT"

 ACCEPT

 Germany's Accept were never going to be as successful as their countrymen
 the Scorpions, but what they did achieve during their halcyon days was
 nothing short of spectacular. Formed in 1977, the band's classic line-up
 consisted of one Udo Dirkschneider (vocals), Wolf Hoffman (guitar),
 Hermann Frank (guitar), Peter Baltes (bass), and Stefan Kaufmann (drums),
 and they came together, it seems, with the express desire to be some sort
 of German @{"Judas Priest" link "JUDAS PRIEST"}. Certainly, they supported the Brummie metallers,
 and some of that polished chrome style rubbed off of them. Very much to
 the fore, the Accept sound boasted Dirkschneider's impossibly shrieked
 and snarled vocals and the bombastic twin riffing of Hoffmann and Franks.
 With this combination already in place, all that was required was some
 serious speed in the rhythm department and you had a proto-thrash band.
 Well, almost, because although their influence on the burgeoning thrash
 scene was evident, this lot trod a more controlled and melodic path.
 This was best exemplified by a stunning clutch of albums - 'Restless
 And Wild', 'Balls To The Wall', 'Metal Heart', 'Russian Roulette' -
 in the early to mid-'80s, which put them at the peak of their game.
 Sadly, Dirkschneider began to think his bandmates were going a little
 soft and he went solo in 1987, leaving them to flounder somewhat with
 a series of different singers. They split in 1989 and then reunited for
 a number of unspectacular metal efforts in the '90s.

 Recommended listening: 'Balls To The Wall'

@endnode


@node "AC-DC"

 AC/DC

 Emerging from some of the roughest, toughest bars in Sydney back in 1973,
 these formidable Aussies have become virtually the biggest hard rock 'n'
 boogie band on the planet. Best known for the visual gimmick of lead
 guitarist Angus Young being dressed as a schoolboy - he literally was at
 school at the time they started - their reputation was, nevertheless,
 sealed by a string of classic albums in the '70s, featuring the unique
 whiskey-soaked rasp of vocalist Bon Scott. For simple, honest-to-goodness
 party-time boogie, AC/DC are, indisputably, the business, as can be
 witnessed on such cracking outings as 'Let There Be Rock', 'Powerage' and
 the world-shaking masterpiece that is 'Highway To Hell', where Scott's
 penchant for lewd 'n' crude, tongue-in-cheek lyrics achieved new heights
 - or should that be lows? - of un-PC vulgarity. Sadly, with the band
 teetering on the cusp of true worldwide recognition, the hard-living
 frontman's rocker lifestyle resulted in his alcohol-related death in
 February 1980. The band continued with ex-Geordie singer Brian Johnson
 for what would become one of the all-time classic albums in rock history,
 'Back In Black'; a weighty, brilliant record the band have struggled,
 somewhat, to match over more recent years.

 Recommended listening: 'Highway To Hell'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "AEROSMITH"

 AEROSMITH

 Few bands epitomise the mythical rock 'n' roll lifestyle with quite the
 same degree of conviction as Aerosmith. The legendary exploits of singer
 Steven Tyler and guitarist Joe Perry - let alone the other members - have
 passed into rock lore and led to them being dubbed the Toxic Twins for
 obvious reasons. Naturally, this would mean nothing were it not for the
 fact that, despite propping up half the Latin American economies through
 their chemical excesses, their hell-raising activities led to some damn
 fine records. Influenced by the blues, early r 'n' b and Motown, these
 five skinny white boys reinterpreted pretty much everything they heard
 as pure, sleazy hard rock, very much in the vein of their heroes the
 Rolling Stones, with a panache that would later be half-inched by the
 likes of world-conquerors @{"Guns N' Roses" link "GUNS N' ROSES"}. Their most successful attempt
 to capture their hedonistic attitude in the '70s was with 'Toys In The
 Attic' - a very loaded album title indeed - and the unsurpassable 'Rocks'.
 Despite a rocky patch in the early '80s, when Perry left to form the
 Joe Perry Music Project, the band reunited and on the back of mega-hit
 'Walk This Way' (with a little help from rap stars Run DMC), relaunched
 themselves. The superbly diverse 'Permanent Vacation', and the slick
 'Pump' saw them rein in the excesses somewhat and reinvent themselves
 as the hard rock band of choice for the MTV generation.

 Recommended listening: 'Toys In The Attic'

@endnode


@node "ALICE COOPER"

 ALICE COOPER

 Alice Cooper the man - aka Vincent Furnier, born the son of a preacher
 - will forever be associated with the timeless teenage rampage of the
 1972 smash hit 'School's Out', but delve a little deeper and you'll
 discover a career punctuated with era-defining moments of hard rock
 genius. Originally Alice Cooper (taking the name, apparently, from
 a 17th century witch) was the name of the entire band - a moniker,
 they used to love telling people, which had been chosen for them by
 a ghostly spirit during a particularly spooky seance. As if that wasn't
 provocative enough to get moral guardians' blood boiling, they pioneered
 a style of trashy, glammy, shock rock, which has since been hijacked
 and bastardised by numerous pretenders to the throne, most notably
 @{"Marilyn Manson" link "MARILYN MANSON"}. Chief among these reputation building albums was the
 deliberately offensive 'Billion Dollar Babies', a mad splurge of brilliance
 celebrating the tacky decadence of '70s society. By 1975, however, the band
 had parted company and ol' Vince adopted the misanthropic Cooper persona
 himself. With legendary producer Bob Ezrin also on board, the usual
 revelling in the depravity of modern culture was sidetracked and they went
 for an overt horror slant instead. The result was the concept album,
 'Welcome To My Nightmare', one of the classiest rock albums to emerge from
 the '70s. The subsequent ten years brought a variety of different styles
 and records of varying quality. but it took 1989's ultra-commercial 'Trash'
 and hit single 'Poison' to brand Alice on the minds of the MTV generation,
 along with a superb cameo appearance in 'Wayne's World'. Since then, albums
 have appeared at regular intervals, the latest, 'Brutal Planet', being
 released in June 2000.

 Recommended listening: 'Welcome To My Nightmare'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "ALICE IN CHAINS"

 ALICE IN CHAINS

 Often unfairly lumped in with the grunge phenomenon, not least because
 they emerged from Seattle in the late '80s, Alice In Chains did, in fact,
 enjoy something of a glammy origin as Diamond Lie around 1985. With those
 pretensions quickly subsumed by a much darker, brooding sound, captured
 most succinctly by guitarist Jerry Cantrell and the bleak vocal and lyrical
 rumblings of Layne Staley, they were clearly a very troubled bunch of lads
 who had obviously been dabbling rather too much with class A narcotics -
 in particular, smack. Whatever their chemical recreational habits, their
 'Facelift' debut was a solid enough affair, but their most dazzling opus
 was 1992's 'Dirt', featuring a number of songs which had already been
 given something of a decent test drive round the club circuit over the
 preceding years. These songs, including 'Dirt' and 'Rooster', would prove
 to be their most enduring, even after the grunge wave began to subside.
 Unfortunately, despite their obvious musical flexibility and creativity
 - witness the weirdly wonderful five-song EP 'Sap' - and their
 protestations that heroin chic was not their bag any more, it now appears
 that drug-induced instability has put the band into effective suspended
 animation for the time being.

 Recommended listening: 'Dirt'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "ANTHRAX"

 ANTHRAX

 Bermuda-shorted cartoon metal buffoons or long-running, defining
 progenitors of thrash? Or both? One of the most enduring bands of the '80s
 thrash wave, Noo Yoikers Anthrax experienced a very dodgy career launch
 with vocalist Neil Turbin and the execrable 'Fistful Of Metal' before
 ditching the loser, adopting the histrionic wail of Joey Belladonna and
 forging ahead at the vanguard of thrash. By the middle of the decade,
 this self-deprecating outfit ranked up there with the likes of @{"Megadeth" link "MEGADETH"}
 and @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"} and their tough, street-level blitz resulted in such genre
 classics as the aptly titled 'Spreading The Disease' and 'Among The
 Living'. Their songs, inspired by everything from futuristic comic book
 cop Judge Dredd and various Stephen King novels (favourite author of
 songwriting guitarist Scott 'Not' Ian) to world peace and the plight of
 native Americans, marked them out as somewhat unique among their peers.
 Indeed, their dabblings with rap - the hit single 'I'm The Man' and the
 Chuck D assisted 'Bring The Noise' - indicated that they were far more
 inventive and flexible than most standard thrash outfits. With Belladonna
 out of the loop in the '90s and ex-Armored Saint singer John Bush as
 frontman, they continued to turn out tough gritty rock albums - such as
 'Sound Of White Noise' and 'Stomp 442' - despite a downturn in their
 fortunes.

 Recommended listening: 'Spreading The Disease'

@endnode


@node "ASIA"

 ASIA

 Though this well-seasoned supergroup continued well into the '90s - with
 the albums 'Aqua' and 'Aria' after a break in the mid '80s - Asia never
 again achieved the same degree of success that greeted them when they
 first formed during the heady days of pomp rock. Back in 1981, Asia
 consisted of well-travelled rockers bassist John Wetton (ex-King Crimson),
 guitarist Steve Howe (ex-Yes), drummer Carl Palmer (ex-Emerson, Lake &
 Palmer) and keyboard player Geoff Downes (ex-Yes and, believe it or not,
 Buggles!). As you would expect from such a motley collection of old-school
 talent, they had a penchant for prog rock noodling par excellence with
 gloriously technical musical passages bringing to mind the genre excesses
 of the '70s. Fortunately, there was also a polished commercial edge to the
 songs and the ultra-smooth AOR pop of their 1982 eponymous debut kicked
 off with the hit single 'Heat Of The Moment'. The pop hits continued to
 flow with follow-up 'Alpha' and singles 'Don't Cry' and 'The Smile Has
 Left Your Eyes', but third album 'Astra' suffered greatly due to the
 disruption caused by line-up changes, a situation they never fully
 recovered from.

 Recommended listening: 'Asia'

@endnode


@node "ATARI TEENAGE RIOT"

 ATARI TEENAGE RIOT

 Speed metal, punk, techno, hardcore, acid house, drum 'n' bass - the list
 goes on and on and on. If you can think of a musical sub-genre, then
 chances are that Berlin noise-art terrorists Atari Teenage Riot have
 probably deployed it in their politically radical stance against racism
 and what they see as the general right wing shift in Western politics
 following the destruction of the Berlin Wall. Formed back in 1992 as
 a direct response to the genre and racial apartheid creeping into Germany's
 youth culture, Alec Empire, Hanin Elias and MC/DJ Carl Crack formed the
 Riot to openly challenge what they saw happening at a street level.
 Their sound featured enormous guitar riffs, impossibly speedy breakbeats
 and a great deal of edgy shouting. Their first single was the remarkable
 'Hunting For Nazis' and immediately marked them out as a band with true
 punk credentials who were in serious danger of giving the protest song
 genre a major shot of badly needed creative energy. Having released
 a number of singles under, ironically, major label Phonogram, they left
 when it became clear the label wanted more straight ahead techno-rock
 from them. With the leftover cash from their advance, in true punk
 fashion, they created Digital Hardcore Recordings and unleashed the
 albums 'Delete Yourself' and 'The Future War', as well as nurturing
 like-minded acts on the new label. The cool cult cache that came with
 such single-minded determination resulted in an inevitable growth in
 stature and support slots on tours with the likes of left-field artist
 Beck. As if confirmation of their staggering originality were need,
 1999's '60 Second Wipeout' was yet another bafflingly intense and
 confrontational blast of adrenalised noise.

 Recommended listening: '60 Second Wipeout'

@endnode


