@node "BAD BRAINS"

 BAD BRAINS

 The outright collision of punk and reggae sounds fairly unlikely as an
 approach to successful music, but if The Clash and their peers could pull
 it off, then why not? That, at least, was the theory behind Bad Brains,
 the outfit created by jazz fusion guitarist Dr Know (aka Gary Miller),
 after being inspired by the rank amateurism of punk and the political
 stance of Bob Marley. With such a radical approach to their sound and the
 volatile nature of street level culture in their hometown of Washington DC
 in the late '70s, Bad Brains quickly stirred up major interest on the
 underground punk scene. They would completely baffle their audiences by
 ripping through such classic early singles as 'Pay To Cum' and 'Big
 Takeover', then slow things down to a truly spiritual pace with some
 seriously heavy reggae, a gear shift ably controlled by vocalist HR's
 impossible vocal gymnastics. And if this approach foxed some people,
 then that was as nothing compared to the confusion caused by their apparent
 inability to release and distribute albums. Their full-length eponymous
 debut was a cassette-only release and it took until 1983's Ric Ocasek
 (The Cars) produced 'Rock For Light' for them to venture on to record.
 Even then, their next album 'I Against I' took almost four years to hit
 the shelves. Such erratic appearances in the public arena were already
 frustrating, but then the inevitable 'musical differences' took their toll,
 with half the band wanting to follow the reggae route and the other half
 opting for rock. The clash eventually led to a number of line-up changes
 from which the group, sadly, never fully recovered, but their overtly
 political influence and daring approach to punk rock is still evident
 in many of today's leading hardcore outfits.

 Recommended listening: 'Rock For Light'

@endnode


@node "BAD COMPANY"

 BAD COMPANY

 Not many bands can boast a career quite as lengthy as Bad Company who
 formed back in 1973 from the disintegrated hard rockers @{"Free" link "FREE"}. With a
 line-up boasting the legendary Paul Rodgers (vocals), Simon Kirke (drums),
 ex-Mott The Hoople fella Mick Ralphs (guitar) and veteran Boz Burrell
 (bass), the band was often unfairly labelled as a soulless version of
 Free, but was actually a lot more successful; witness worldwide hit
 'Can't Get Enough' and superb albums such as their eponymous debut,
 'Straight Shooter' and 'Run With the Pack'. Hugely admired by @{"Led Zeppelin" link "LED ZEPPELIN"},
 they supported them on tour and eventually signed to their famed Swan Song
 label. With their tough, raw, bluesy sound, they effectively pioneered the
 slick and melodic hard rock sound that was polished to a commercial gleam
 by such AOR legends as Foreigner. Unfortunately, the late '70s and early
 '80s brought internal friction and a loss of momentum, even though they
 continued to be a major commercial success. Rodgers left to work with
 Jimmy Page in the Firm and the band continued with an ever-shifting
 line-up until last year, when all the original members were reunited for
 an extremely successful tour.

 Recommended listening: 'Bad Co.'

@endnode


@node "BAD RELIGION"

 BAD RELIGION

 Southern California's Bad Religion are one of those rare entities -
 a hardcore punk band that have actually retained their underground
 credibility, while at the same time reaching massive audiences by
 eventually signing a major label deal. Formed back in 1980, the band was
 typical of the hardcore scene at the time, although there were inklings
 that their sheer talent and brazen attitude would take them well beyond
 their competent debut, 1983's 'Into The Unknown'. Interestingly, guitarist
 Brad Gurewitz established Epitaph Records around this time in order to
 release the band's product, with the result that it is now possibly the
 biggest punk label in the world (thanks mainly to the hit album 'Smash'
 provided by the @{"Offspring" link "OFFSPRING"}). Back in the '80s, the label was just a means
 to an end - it allowed the band to remain independent and creatively sharp,
 a fact borne out by their righteously angry polemics aimed squarely at the
 ills of modern society. By the early '90s, the band had progressed
 considerably to incorporate a slightly more rock-oriented sound, and
 signed to a major label. 1993's 'Recipe For Hate' album was originally
 released on Epitaph, but was re-released with help of Atlantic.
 The result was that Bad Religion were an 'alternative' band sitting
 happily in the mainstream. Whether this relaxation of musical demarcation
 lines was due to the grunge wave is, in a sense, irrelevant, because it
 allowed the band to reach a much wider audience without diluting the power
 of their convictions.

 Recommended listening: 'Against The Grain'

@endnode


@node "BIOHAZARD"

 BIOHAZARD

 Tattoos, anger, lots of shouting, a wall of guitars, more tattoos, more
 shouting - if you're looking for smoochy, lighter-raising ballads and
 smooth pop rock, look away now. Because Biohazard bring the whole weight
 of modern urban decay with themselves into the studio whenever they record.
 And when we're talking about decay, we mean the roughest, most bruising
 experiences you can imagine from their formative area, Brooklyn, Noo Yoik.
 Formed back in 1988, they were driven by the social injustices they
 witnessed every day and their early sound was very similar to other
 New York hardcore stalwarts and heavily influenced by the likes of @{"Anthrax" link "ANTHRAX"}.
 However, naturally open to the sounds on the street, hip-hop gradually
 seeped into the mix and their 1990 self-titled debut found them
 experimenting gamely with their songwriting. By the time of 1992's
 indignantly enraged 'Urban Discipline', the synthesis of thrash and beats
 was virtually complete. Subsequent albums, 'State Of The World Address',
 'Mata Leao' and live album 'No Holds Barred', merely thrashed the already
 tightly honed intensity into yet more and varied permutations. It seemed
 almost impossible for the band to maintain such a ferociously focused
 attack and yet in 1999, they released possibly their most confrontational
 album yet, 'New World Disorder'. While there is injustice in the world,
 it seems that there will always be a niche for Biohazard.

 Recommended listening: 'Urban Discipline'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'State of the World Address'

@endnode


@node "BLACK SABBATH"

 BLACK SABBATH

 With their roots in the heavy blues scene of the late '60s, the band that
 effectively defined heavy metal in the '70s originally rejoiced under the
 unlikely moniker of Earth. Taking their name from a horror movie based on
 a Dennis Wheatley novel, they set about making a name for themselves by
 adopting an overtly extreme (for the period) horror stance as a stark
 contrast to the hippy-drippy excesses of the '60s and early '70s.
 Guitarist Tony Iommi rapidly developed a reputation as a human riff machine
 and with the bowel-loosening rhythmic engine of bassist Geezer Butler and
 drummer Bill Ward at their core, their sound set the standard all other
 metal bands would seek to emulate. Of course, the fact that one of rock's
 original mad men, the peerless @{"Ozzy Osbourne" link "OZZY OSBOURNE"}, was on vocals gave them an
 undeniable head start and the band blazed a trail with a series of
 doom-laden classics: their eponymous debut album, 'Paranoid' (featuring
 that hit single), 'Master Of Reality', 'Volume 4', 'Sabbath Bloody Sabbath'
 and 'Sabotage'. In 1978, with the pressure of narcotics and success
 weighing heavily upon them, Osbourne left to pursue a solo career while
 the band continued with singer @{"Ronnie James Dio" link "DIO"} (ex-@{"Rainbow" link "RAINBOW"} and Elf).
 Sadly, the line-up fractured further until Iommi was the only original
 member at the creative helm of a number of decidedly average albums in
 the '80s and '90s. More recently, however, with hatchets firmly buried,
 the original line-up reformed to perform once again to unanimous worldwide
 acclaim.

 Recommended listening: 'Sabbath Bloody Sabbath'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Paranoid'

@endnode


@node "BLUE OYSTER CULT"

 BLUE OYSTER CULT

 Baffling, bombastic, beguiling - all these and many more seemingly
 incongruous qualities can be attributed to New York's Blue Oyster Cult;
 after all, who else could write songs about sex, sci-fi and Godzilla
 and make some of the most absurd lyrics sound like poetry? After a shaky
 start in 1969, sneakily began to adopt the accoutrements of mysticism
 and the occult so readily associated with them now; the chaos symbol, the
 deliberately ironic lyrics and an intentionally provocative approach to
 their artwork. Throughout the '70s, under the guidance of writer/producer
 Sandy Pearlman, the band found themselves not only admired by headbangers
 worldwide, but by anyone who appreciated their particularly arty brand
 of metal - especially anyone turned on, bizarrely, by the lyrical
 contributions of punk poetess Patti Smith who was going out with keyboard
 player Alan Lanier, a paradox that must still confuse anyone who likes
 their music easily catagorised. Without doubt, the one single song that
 catapulted to international stardom was their massive hit '(Don't Fear)
 The Reaper' which took the US by storm in 1976 and the UK charts in 1978.
 And the mid '70s was definitely their most creatively successful period,
 featuring such idiosyncratic masterpieces as 'Secret Treaties' and
 'Agents Of Fortune'. Sadly, their lucky star began to wane and the
 albums gradually became patchier through the '80s and '90s, though they
 courageously continue to play live.

 Recommended listening: 'Agents of Fortune'

@endnode


@node "BODY COUNT"

 BODY COUNT

 At first it seems highly unlikely that a successful and credible hip-hop
 star such as Ice-T would dabble with the hoary old world of hard rock
 and heavy metal. After all, if everyone loves you for being (at least
 musically) the cool antithesis of cliched rock, why change? Nevertheless,
 Ice-T first met guitarist Ernie C at Crenshaw High School and continued to
 consul him whenever a vicious guitar riff was required as their respective
 musical careers got underway. As a result, Body Count officially came into
 existence in 1989 and were blowing people away on the very first
 Lollapalooza tour before they'd even recorded an album. When 'Body Count'
 emerged, it was an amazing amalgamation of thundering metal and Ice-T's
 brazen, tongue-in-cheek lyrics honed from years of the hippest hip-hop.
 As a crossover album, it was unique, but nothing could have prepared the
 band for the song that really broke them into the popular consciousness.
 While some of the tracks were just throwaways, one of the more serious
 songs provoked outrage and made it the most notorious tune to ever
 (dis)grace a record. 'Cop Killer' had the moral guardians and political
 authorities up in arms and eventually provoked the record label to remove
 the tune from the album after the band and label personnel received death
 threats. Subsequent albums 'Born Dead' and 'Violent Demise: Last Days'
 were more of the same, only without any tunes garnering the same degree
 of outrage, and the band have been relatively quiet of late.

 Recommended listening: 'Body Count'
                        (the version with 'Cop Killer'- if you can find it!)

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode

@node "BON JOVI"

 BON JOVI

 A strict adherent to the don't-bore-us-get-to-the-chorus school of
 songwriting, Jon Bon Jovi (a softening of family name Bongiovi) was a
 desperate individual trying to get a solo career launched in the early
 '80s. With his photogenic good looks and penchant for self-marketing,
 however, it was just a matter of time before the world took notice.
 With school pal David Bryan (keyboards) on board, they then gathered
 Richie Sambora (guitar), Alec John Such (bass) and Ticco Torres (drums)
 around them, and all the pieces were in place for international stardom.
 An eponymous debut and follow-up, '7800 °F', failed to get Bon Jovi
 anything more than a few decent reviews and a whole lot of indifference,
 but all that would change in 1986, when top producer Bruce Fairburn began
 to shape their third album with the help of some major songwriting talent,
 most notably Desmond Child whose slick tricks with lyrics and melody were
 legendary. In the decade of spandex, glitzy silk scarves and poodle perms,
 Jon had it all - and now he had the solid gold album he craved.
 'Slippery When Wet' was pure commercial dynamite - 'You Give Love A Bad
 Name', 'Livin' On A Prayer', 'Wanted Dead Or Alive' - it was packed with
 anthemic pop rock gems, and Jon was now the mythical cowboy troubadour,
 charming everyone with his stadium-filling antics. The follow-up,
 'New Jersey', proved to be yet another album in this tried-and-tested
 mould.  Inevitably, grunge took its toll on the band in the early '90s,
 and with a series of publicly reported disagreements about royalties
 between the man himself and Sambora, the band looked ready to split.
 A situation not helped by the release of Jon's soundtrack to 'Blaze Of
 Glory - Young Guns II', which contained the smash hit 'Blaze Of Glory'.
 However, Jon was nothing if not a supremely cunning businessman, and the
 band re-emerged in 1992 with 'Keep The Faith', sporting fashionably
 shorter hair cuts and a tougher, yet still hugely commercial, sound.
 Since then, band work has alternated with solo outings, and they are set
 to release 'Crush' in summer 2000.

 Recommended listening: 'Slippery When Wet'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "BOSTON"

 BOSTON

 This extraordinary melodic hard rock band, led by the musical perfectionist
 Tom Scholz, were one of the least prolific, yet most highly influential,
 bands of the '70s and '80s. Formed in the mid '70s by studio technician
 and multi-instrumentalist Scholz, Boston's main artistic thrust was the
 creation of perfectly crafted songs through the deployment of technology
 in the studio, and debut album 'Boston' (1976) is a testament to this
 meticulous sonic engineering. The album was brimful of solid harmonies
 and driving guitar, nowhere more apparent than on its monster smash hit
 single 'More Than A Feeling'. The effect of this melodic marvel was
 extremely far-reaching - as has been often pointed out, @{"Nirvana" link "NIRVANA"}'s 'Smell's
 Like Teen Spirit' owes just as much to that famous riff as to any number
 of obscure punk bands. The irony of the Boston situation, however, is
 that Scholz's notorious perfectionism got the better of him and while
 1978's follow-up 'Don't Look Back' was also a hit (albeit on a lesser
 scale), it took until 1986 and 'Third Stage' for the band to release
 another album. Although this record gave them the US No. 1 hit single
 'Amanda', Scholz had succeeded in alienating his band and record label
 along the way. In 1994, they got around to releasing their fourth album.
 'Walk On'. and who knows when they might release a fifth?

 Recommended listening: 'Boston'

