@node "CANNIBAL CORPSE"

 CANNIBAL CORPSE

 'If you want blood - you've got it!' sang @{"AC/DC" link "AC-DC"}'s Bon Scott many years
 back and with Cannibal Corpse, you've definitely got it. Lots of it.
 Splashed all over the place. Along with brains, entrails, and a still
 pumping heart. Possibly one of the most deliberately offensive and deeply
 unpleasant death metal bands to ever commit aural butchery to tape,
 Cannibal Corpse first rose from the dead in Buffalo, New York, in 1988.
 The city's underground metal scene was humming with activity and none were
 more active than this lot who pinched the nastiest, speediest bits from
 Slayer and proceeded to add their own unique flourishes to the sound.
 As if the unadulterated brutality of the music weren't enough, the band
 revelled in the most obscenely indecipherable lyrical matter their twisted
 little minds could conjure up. Hence they penned charming little ditties
 like 'Entrails Ripped From A Virgin's Cunt', 'I Cum Blood' and 'Meathook
 Sodomy'. These playful tunes could be found on albums such as debut
 'Eaten Back To Life', 1991's 'Butchered At Birth' and 1992's catchily
 titled 'Tomb Of The Mutilated'. Not happy with just aural violence,
 the sleeve artwork also featured all manner of hideous splatter and gore,
 which inevitably resulted in various albums being banned from major
 retailing chains. Naturally, a cult following was inevitable with
 successive albums and, bizarrely, they can even be seen as a club band
 in the Jim Carrey comedy 'Ace Ventura: Pet Detective'!

 Recommended listening: 'Tomb Of the Mutilated'

@endnode


@node "CARCASS"

 CARCASS

 A suitably graphic name for a seriously graphic band. In terms of extreme
 music, Carcass were pioneers in the thrash sub-genre known as grindcore,
 a style developed from the short, sharp shocks churned out by the likes
 of Napalm Death, topped off by larynx-ripping guttural roars. In fact,
 the band shared guitarist Bill Steer with Napalm Death until their third
 album, when he became singly devoted to the cause of hardcore gore.
 In terms of subject matter, all they needed to do was raid a medical
 textbook for some of the most stomach-churning imagery imaginable,
 absolutely guaranteed to get your bile rising with its technically precise
 terminology. As for their artwork - well, that concentrated on ironic
 splatter too, and graced such gloriously grotesque outings as their 1988
 debut 'Reek Of Putrefaction', follow-up 1989's 'Symphonies Of Sickness'
 and 1991's absurdly twisted 'Necrotism: Descanting The Insalubrious'.
 Sitting proudly on these albums, the avid gore freak would find such
 tender-hearted singalongs as 'Excoriating Abdominal Emanation',
 'Crepitating Bowel Erosion', and the catchily named 'Cadaveric Incubator
 Of Endo-Parasites'. Gradually the band began to move away from outright
 brutality and introduced such radical concepts as melody and accessibility.
 Unfortunately, this shift in ideals signalled that the end was in sight
 and founding member Steer departed after 1996's 'Swansong' album.

 Recommended listening: 'Necrotism: Descanting The Insalubrious'

 ZUBI/s recommended listening: 'Heartwork'

@endnode


@node "CATHEDRAL"

 CATHEDRAL

 Napalm Death isn't exactly the type of band one would expect to figure in
 the formation of the UK's foremost doom 'n' stoner outfit. Nevertheless
 when vocalist Lee Dorrian formed Napalm Death he always nurtured a love
 of stoned-out riffs and monster flares, and it was this infatuation with
 all things tackily 70s that motivated the man to create Cathedral in 1990.
 'Forest Of Equilibrium' was their fine debut of 1991 and proved to be
 a cornucopia of fantasy and sci-fi inspired lyricism nailed down by
 a knowing sense of gloomy rhythm and a healthy dose of self-deprecating
 irony. Follow-ups, 1993's 'The Ethereal Mirror' and 1995's 'The Carnival
 Bizarre' - along with some fine EPs and singles - placed them firmly at
 the top of the doom heap, with Dorrian's lyrical obsessions knowing no
 bounds, encompassing everything from black magic to a love of Hammer
 horror movies. With 1996's 'Supernatural Birth Machine' and 1998's
 'Caravan Beyond Redemption' the band's previously Sabbath-esque sound
 had evolved to include everything from splashes of heavy funk to -
 bizarrely - disco death. Quite extraordinary.

 Recommended listening: The Carnival Bizarre

@endnode


@node "CELTIC FROST"

 CELTIC FROST

 Not many thrash outfits of the mid '80s could claim to be particularly
 innovative when it came to musical direction, but for Swiss outfit Celtic
 Frost, led by the enigmatic Tom G Warrior, invention was the very life
 blood of creation. Formed in 1984 from the wreckage of the distinctly below
 average Hellhammer, Celtic Frost would go on to become something of both
 a commercial and critical success. At first, they adopted a fairly standard
 studs 'n' leather stance, completed with some judicious application of
 make-up, for 'Morbid Tales'. Warrior deployed his famous death grunts to
 terrific effect and the songs were suitably gothic while possessing all
 the chaotic energy of thrash. Follow-up 'To Mega Therion' contained further
 stabs into art rock territory, but with 1987's 'Into The Pandemonium',
 Warrior and his cohorts had created something unique. There were sections
 of poetry present alongside orchestration, Eastern prayer chants and,
 even more bizarrely, rap! This was imagination run riot - not bad going
 for a band that had started off in the mould of Slayer. Unfortunately,
 1988's 'Cold Lake' went for a more mainstream glam style sound, which
 alienated many of their fans, so when they reverted to type with
 'Vanity/Nemesis', the damage had already been done and they split
 a little while later. Most recently, Tom Fischer (Warrior's real name)
 has masterminded the creation of cyber-metallers Apollyon Sun.

 Recommended listening: 'Into The Pandemonium'

@endnode


@node "CHEAP TRICK"

 CHEAP TRICK

 Bands with even a fraction of Cheap Trick's style and intelligence are,
 sadly, extremely thin on the ground. This four-piece from the appropriately
 named Rockford, Illinois, first emerged in the mid '70s and at the pinnacle
 of their success were admired just as much by devout fans as by other
 musicians.  With an image that was equal parts sex appeal (vocalist Robin
 Zander and bassist Tom Petersson) and court jester (drummer Bun E Carlos
 and guitarist Rick Nielsen), these lads brought both humour and style to
 their music - an aspect personified by the madcap Nielsen in his trademark
 goofy jumpers, bow tie and baseball cap. Naturally, this would all be as
 nothing were it not for some marvellously hooky hard-rocking albums;
 in particular, 1977's 'In Color', and '78's 'Heaven Tonight'.
 Of particular note was their glorious gig document 'Live At Budokan',
 where all the seemingly disparate elements of the Trick combined to
 staggering effect. In the '80s, the band were, unfortunately, less
 successful and, somewhat ironically, it took a bunch of outside songwriters
 to give them some commercial clout again with 1988's super-smooth
 'Lap Of Luxury' and their first ever US No. 1 'The Flame'. Since then,
 it fair to say that, though the band have bravely continued, they seem
 to be merely treading creative water.

 Recommended listening: 'Live At Budokan'

@endnode


@node "CINDIRELLA"

 CINDERELLA

 More glam than an explosion in a glitter factory, with a name like
 Cinderella you knew exactly what you were going to get with this good-time
 party outfit. Formed in 1984 and led by vocalist/guitarist Tom Keiffer
 this four-piece put in many a sweaty night in the bars and clubs of
 Philadelphia before being championed by one @{"Jon Bon Jovi" link "BON JOVI"}. At this point
 precisely the band became dead certs in the big-haired 80s and debut album
 'Night Songs' (1986) was a quintessential product of the times. It took
 the trash ethics of @{"Motley Crue" link "MOTLEY CRUE"} gave them an @{"AC/DC" link "AC-DC"} twist and, with the
 likes of MTV hit 'Shake Me', lit the blue touch paper. They were loud,
 raucous and the perfect tour accompaniment for the likes of @{"David Lee Roth" link "DAVID LEE ROTH"}
 and Bon Jovi. Follow-up 1988's 'Long Cold Winter' showed a greater
 diversity and it was this desire to move away from pop metal that
 ironically converted the critics but lost them their fans, who obviously
 loved the no-brain rockers more than their carefully wrought third album
 'Heartbreak Station'. The band were now going for a more flexible, bluesy,
 Rolling Stones sound which obviously baffled anyone who simply wanted to
 get their rocks off. Since then Cinderella have faded considerably with
 only 1994's 'Still Climbing' a solid reminder of their 80s glory days.

 Recommended listening: 'Night Songs'

@endnode


@node "COAL CHAMBER"

 COAL CHAMBER

 Edgy, disturbing, bizarre - just a few of the many, and valid, ways of
 describing LA angst-fiends Coal Chamber. Formed in 1994 by Dez Fafara
 (vocals) and Miguel 'Meegs' Rascon (guitar), who met by answering
 a classified ad, they added Mike Cox (drums) and Rayna Foss (bass) before
 building up a reputation for impassioned and cathartic live shows at venues
 such as the Roxy and Whiskey A-Go-Go. Their demo tape also garnered a great
 deal of interest, not least because it was championed by @{"Fear Factory" link "FEAR FACTORY"}'s
 Dino Cazares. When their eponymous 1997 debut emerged, it finally became
 clear why Coal Chamber had struck a nerve with such accuracy. The record
 was by turns spiteful, angry and fearlessly innovative - it also contained
 a major alternative hit in 'Loco'. It borrowed the grungy downtuned fire of
 acts such as @{"Korn" link "KORN"}, threw in some cool hip-hop influenced rhythmic twists,
 all finished off with Fafara's decidedly unique vocals. This was the sound
 of trauma committed to tape. It was also very, very heavy indeed. Always
 keen to remain industrious, the band then toured for what seemed like an
 age before returning with 'Chamber Music' (1999), and a direction that
 adopted a more arty, gothic feel to their already fearsome sound.

 Recommended listening: 'Chamber Music'

