@node "CORROSION OF CONFORMITY"

 CORROSION OF CONFORMITY

 A very apt name for a band who perform with such ingrained integrity,
 Corrosion Of Conformity have actually been working their way towards
 a heavy 'stoner' style vibe ever since their inception as a hardcore band
 back in the very early 80s. Back then founding member, guitarist Woody
 Weatherman created a band intent on delivering the hardest, toughest
 politically charged polemic they could, but the band's sound was never
 quite satisfactory even though albums such as 'Animosity' and 'Technocracy'
 still sound solid today. It took the addition of New Orleans-raised
 Pepper Keenan (guitar/vocals) and his unique musical voice to give COC the
 necessary push into a new creative direction. COC didn't exactly become
 a 'stoner' band as such - not for them the flares and unequivocal love of
 all things 70s - rather they adopted the sludgey, fuzzy power of, say,
 @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"} but twisted it to a very 90s template with albums such as
 'Blind', 'Deliverance' and, their real breakthrough record, 1996's
 devastatingly powerful 'Wiseblood'. With it came COC's jump up into the
 general rock consciousness and the band enjoyed major exposure supporting
 the likes of @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"} on their 'Load' world tour. Since then things have
 become relatively quiet, though Keenan's love of 'timeless' rock can also
 be sampled on 'Down', a project which also included @{"Pantera" link "PANTERA"}'s Phil Anselmo.

 Recommended listening: 'Wiseblood'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Deliverence'

