@node "CRADLE OF FILTH"

 CRADLE OF FILTH

 When it comes to the blackest of black metal the UK's Cradle Of Filth
 could give some of the nastiest Scandinavian outfits a real run for their
 money.  Formed in 1991, in Ipswich, the one constant feature of the band
 throughout a series of personnel changes is the guiding leadership of
 vocalist Dani Filth. With his eardrum-savaging vocal style - somewhere
 between a cat's screech and a terrier's yap - Filth has shaped the
 direction the band has taken right from their first forays into gothic
 thrash right up to their latest conceptual album, 1998's 'Cruelty And
 The Beast'. In the interim the band have released such dark delights
 as mini-LP 'Vempire Or Dark Faerytales In Phallustein' and the album
 'Dusk & Her Embrace'. In building up to 'Cruelty...' - surely some kind
 of artistic pinnacle for the genre - the band have developed from overt
 thrash roots to incorporating a more considered and deliberately arty
 orchestral approach to their tales of satanic debauchery. In particular,
 they have taken the hitherto underground goth vampire image and given the
 myth a commercial twist by adopting the look themselves for the fashion
 conscious 90s, and in the process spawned a whole slew of imitators.
 Not only that, but Filth's literary tastes have given the band a definite
 edge when it comes to lyrics and concepts; some of the wordplay may be
 self-consciously painful but it has ensured that Cradle Of Filth are
 streets ahead of the competition.

 Recommended listening: 'Cruelty And The Beast'

@endnode


@node "CRO-MAGS"

 CRO-MAGS

 When hardcore was emerging from the underground back in the early '80s,
 New York's Cro-Mags were one of the main outfits that exemplified the
 tight, brutal noise of righteous indignation and championed a positive
 personal philosophy. Not that you'd think it to look at them. Lots of
 tattoos, fists and plenty of macho shouting - while hardcore provided
 the key to their modest success, it was the incorporation of elements
 of thrash metal that really launched them as influential movers and
 shakers. Two members that will forever be connected not only with the
 Cro-Mags - incidentally, that's short for Cro-Magnon man - but to the
 hardcore scene in general, were bassist/bandleader Harley Flanagan and
 lead singer/shouter John 'Bloodclot' Joseph. What's more, they were
 members of the Hare Krishna sect; hence the spiritual positivism espoused
 in many of the songs. When debut album 'The Age Of Quarrel' was released
 in 1986, the band had in one fell swoop established an uncompromising
 identity for themselves, but, unfortunately, the line-up was very volatile
 and so failed to maintain momentum for any meaningful length of time,
 although 'Best Wishes' did follow three years later. Work eventually began
 on 'Alpha-Omega', but it took a split and reformation before it was finally
 finished for release in 1992. In the end, 1993's 'Near Death Experience'
 proved to be the band's swansong as the various members effectively fell
 out with each other for the last time.

 Recommended listening: 'The Age Of Quarrel'

