@node "DAVID LEE ROTH"

 DAVID LEE ROTH

 Teeth, teeth, as far as the eye could see and then there was the hair,
 and the extremely tight, lunchbox-enhancing trousers. Perennial good-time
 rock 'n' roller Diamond Dave sure knew what his audience wanted and, more
 to the point, just how to dish it up. Fronting one of the biggest rock
 bands in the world, the awesome @{"Van Halen" link "VAN HALEN"}, had taught him a thing or two
 over the years, so when he went solo in 1985 with his 'Crazy From The
 Heat' EP, he just concentrated on what he knew best - entertainment -
 delivering fun and glitz in vaudeville and Broadway fashion. His style,
 best typified by 1986's gloriously dynamic 'Eat 'Em And Smile' album,
 was so colourful many people thought he would long outshine his former
 bandmates. He had the charisma and the wit, he looked and sounded
 fantastic, and he didn't care who knew it! With the phenomenal guitar
 talents of @{"Steve Vai" link "STEVE VAI"} at his side, he turned out yet another magical set
 of tunes in 1988's 'Skyscraper', all dazzling fretwork and big, bold,
 chest-beating choruses. Sadly, however, though the records were solid
 enough, Roth's fortunes gradually dipped with subsequent albums, until,
 incredibly, Van Halen hit a rough patch and ol' Roth was back in the frame.
 An album is, apparently, not far off.

 Recommended listening: 'Eat 'Em And Smile'

