@node "DEATH"

 DEATH

 The name says it all really. Formed back in 1983, the architect of the
 Death sound was one Chuck Schuldiner who, over the years to come, would
 prove to be the single constant member of the band, often referred to as
 a dictator surrounded by hired hands. Formed at the inception of the
 thrash metal genre, Death marked themselves out as unique by being the
 most single-mindedly intense outfit in the violence stakes.
 The concentration on all things deathly eventually led to the coining
 of the 'death metal' sub-genre and, although it took them four years to
 release an album - they built their reputation solely through brutal live
 performances and a series of underground tapes - when 'Scream Bloody Gore'
 finally emerged in 1987, Schuldiner and co had created something of a
 thrash masterpiece. Subsequent albums concentrated on the same bloody
 template with the playing gradually becoming increasingly refined and
 relatively technical, until, by the time 'Individual Thought Patterns'
 was released in 1993, the band had actually embraced melody. Well, sort
 of. Definitely an outfit hard to beat in terms of outright, relentless
 thrash, they never made the same commercial impact as some of their peers,
 but remained underground heroes of the genre.

 Recommended listening: 'Scream Bloody Gore'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Human'

@endnode


@node "DEEP PURPLE"

 DEEP PURPLE

 Yes, that guitar riff! Right up there with @{"Led Zep's" link "LED ZEPPELIN"} 'Stairway To Heaven',
 possibly the most mangled song in rock history and favourite of sad musos
 who hang out in guitar shops - the immortal 'Smoke On The Water'.
 The initial Mark I Deep Purple line-up - featuring legendary guitarist
 Ritchie Blackmore and keyboard player Jon Lord - created three rather
 dated-sounding albums in the late '60s, but this period did give them
 another live favourite in their cover of Joe South's 'Hush'. The Mark II
 line-up - featuring the golden larynx of Ian Gillan - was quite spectacular
 by comparison and turned out consistently superb albums such as 'In Rock',
 'Fireball' and 'Machine Head' (home to the classic 'Smoke On The Water').
 Blackmore's frenetic guitar style was perfectly complemented by both Lord's
 massive washes of Hammond organ and Gillan's piercing operatic voice.
 However, even as the band were rapidly becoming one of the hottest acts
 in the world with their powerful bluesy brand of rock, internal friction
 - often blamed on 'moody' Blackmore - had them foundering. Hence the first
 Mark III album to feature David Coverdale (vocals) and Glenn Hughes (bass)
 was 1974's magnificent 'Burn'. But Blackmore was still not happy and so
 left to be replaced by the mercurial guitar talent of Tommy Bolin for just
 one Mark IV studio album, 'Come Taste The Band' (1975). Sadly, the band
 very soon after imploded and Bolin died of a heroin overdose. From this
 mess, of course, such phenomenal outfits as @{"Whitesnake" link "WHITESNAKE"} and @{"Rainbow" link "RAINBOW"} were
 born, but the Purple were not completely dead yet. The fan clamour for
 the band to reform grew year on year until the Mark II line-up could resist
 no longer and 1984 brought 'Perfect Strangers'. Though subsequent years
 have resulted in albums and tours of varying quality, the line-up has
 shifted several times since and now features Steve Morse on guitar.
 The band have recently played London's Royal Albert Hall, recreating their
 30 year old 'Concerto For Group And Orchestra'.

 Recommended listening: 'Machine Head'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

