@node "DEF LEPPARD"

 DEF LEPPARD

 One of the few bands to truly epitomise the MTV-friendly style of stadium
 rock of the '80s, Sheffield's Def Leppard are one of the biggest bands of
 the last twenty years and though their star faded somewhat in the early
 '90s, their current return to hard-rocking form bodes well for the future.
 Starting out in 1977 as Atomic Mass, and influenced by the likes of @{"Queen" link "QUEEN"}
 and Mott The Hoople, the band famously used a disused spoon factory for
 rehearsals as they developed their sound, finalised their line-up and
 changed their name to a more familiar Deaf Leopard. With the now classic
 'Getcha Rocks Off' EP, the band suddenly found themselves catapulted to
 the forefront of the burgeoning New Wave Of British Heavy Metal.
 A quickly recorded debut, 'On Through The Night' (1980), with @{"Judas Priest" link "JUDAS PRIEST"}
 producer Tom Allom, captured the band's sparky youth perfectly and landed
 them US support slots with the likes of Priest and @{"Ted Nugent" link "TED NUGENT"}. This
 apparent defection to the States irritated many of their early fans, but
 the Leps made their first foray into MTV with 'Bringin' On The Heartbreak'
 from the Mutt Lange produced album 'High 'N' Dry'. Lange's production work
 was still relatively unknown, but his obvious skill with a commercial sound
 helped to give the Leps their big break which came, finally, with another
 Lange collaboration, 'Pyromania', a world-conquering smash in 1983.
 With its slick production, massive singalong choruses and keen ear for
 commerciality, 'Pyromania' broke the band to a worldwide audience, but
 disaster was to keep them from releasing a follow-up for four years. First,
 pre-production work with producer Jim Steinman worked out badly and then
 a real catastrophe occurred, when drummer Rick Allen was involved in an
 horrific car accident which severed his left arm. Allen, nevertheless,
 remained in the band, playing his part on a synthesised drum kit operated
 mainly by pedals. When 'Hysteria' was finally released in 1987, the band
 had truly entered the superleague, only to be almost thwarted again when
 guitarist Steve 'Steamin'' Clark was found dead in early 1991 from a lethal
 cocktail of pills and alcohol. His replacement was veteran six-stringer
 Vivian Campbell. 1992's 'Adrenalize' was their last great album in terms
 of profile as the nascent grunge scene overshadowed the Leps and many
 of their peers. After a couple of less notable recent efforts, 1999's
 'Euphoria' marked a return to their classic melodic sound.

 Recommended listening: 'Pyromania'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Hysteria'

