@node "DEICIDE"

 DEICIDE

 Any thrash fans out there who feel that @{"Venom" link "VENOM"} are a bunch of pansies or
 that @{"Slayer" link "SLAYER"} are just a little too soft these days ought to try Deicide on
 for size. Formed back in 1987 as part of the ever-growing Florida death
 metal scene Deicide were a bunch who walked it just like they talked it.
 Taking the early cartoon Satanism of bands like Venom to new extremes,
 band leader, bassist and vocalist Glenn Benton set about creating one of
 the most brutally unpleasant thrash bands currently upsetting sensitive
 people in the world today. It wasn't enough just to throw a few infernal
 images around the place or to have your picture taken surrounded by skulls
 and pentagrams, you actually had to be in league with the horned one
 downstairs. Hence, Benton took to branding an inverted cross on his
 forehead and claimed he and his band were genuine, blood-drinking,
 virgin-sacrificing Satanists. His real media coup came in 1992 when he
 claimed to torture animals as well, which resulted in all sorts of threats
 from enraged animals rights groups. Still, however dubious some of the
 man's claims may have been, when it came to the music, Deicide were very
 much a unique prospect, as can be witnessed on their 1990 self-titled
 debut. They were fast, very fast. And savage. And downright nasty.
 All qualities which were sharpened on subsequent releases, such as
 'Legion' and 'Once Upon The Cross'. Although all the albums featured
 graphic Christian-baiting imagery, the latter had one of their most
 extreme sleeves: a picture of a crucified Christ on an autopsy table.
 The only thing that may stop Deicide from pursuing their deranged campaign
 against decency is death, although even that is unlikely - Benton claimed
 he wanted to be dead by the time he was 33. He's now past that age, and
 the band just keep on going.

 Recommended listening: 'Legion'

@endnode


@node "DIAMOND HEAD"

 DIAMOND HEAD

 Some bands are destined to be huge on the world stage, and some end up
 providing the inspirational fuel to get them there. Diamond Head would
 appear to fall into the latter category. They never sold millions of
 records, they never embarked on worldwide sold-out live tours, but their
 ferociously original style of metal was to influence some of the biggest
 bands currently playing today and as such, demand some serious
 investigation. The original line-up of Sean Harris (vocals), Brian Tatler
 (guitar), Colin Kimberly (bass) and Duncan Scott (drums) originally met at
 school in the mid '70s. Through a series of classic live shows and
 independently produced and solid releases, they rapidly became national
 rock heroes. Early singles included highly collectible masterpieces such
 as 'Shoot Out The Lights/Helpless' and 'Sweet And Innocent/Streets Of
 Gold', and their first album was a white label promo effort called
 'Lightning To The Nations'. In their brashness, they even once famously
 compared themselves to the mighty @{"Led Zeppelin" link "LED ZEPPELIN"}, but their boldness was
 well justified, what with Tatler's gargantuan guitar talent and Harris'
 awesome lung power, they were naturals in the New Wave Of British Heavy
 Metal. Having signed to MCA, however, things began to go a little
 pear-shaped. The label didn't really know how to manage them and their
 first 'proper' album, 'Borrowed Time', took too long to release, while
 other bands such as @{"Iron Maiden" link "IRON MAIDEN"} already had a headstart on them.
 New album 'Canterbury' followed in 1983 and was some way distant from
 their metal beginnings. That and a poor performance at the Donington
 Monsters Of Rock Festival didn't help. Sadly, it all went downhill
 thereafter, and the band were dropped by MCA and split in 1985. In the
 intervening years, the legend of Diamond Head has grown, with such
 megastars as @{"Megadeth" link "MEGADETH"} and @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"} (especially drummer Lars Ulrich)
 championing the band as formative influences. Hence in 1993 Diamond Head
 made a comeback, of sorts, with the valiant 'Death And Progress' album.
 As for their legacy, put it this way: Metallica still crank out the
 monstrous 'Am I Evil?' whenever they play live. 'Nuff said.

 Recommended listening: 'Lightning To The Nations'

@endnode


@node "DIO"

 DIO

 The little man with the big, big voice, singer Ronnie James Dio is,
 ironically, one of the biggest players in the world of metal. His lengthy
 career stretches back into the '60s, but his first real taste of success
 came fronting the preposterously monikered Electric Elves, later sensibly
 shortened to the more economical Elf. His major break came in fronting
 Ritchie Blackmore's @{"Rainbow" link "RAINBOW"} in the '70s, where his soaring operatic voice
 and penchant for ridiculously overwrought lyrics, usually including
 references to rock 'n' roll children and rainbows, began to develop with
 a vengeance. Having filled in for a departed @{"Ozzy Osbourne" link "OZZY OSBOURNE"} in @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"}
 (in the late '70s), he went on to form a metal outfit in his own image,
 a band that would actually commercially outstrip Iommi and cohorts in the
 '80s. Much of Dio's success can be laid not only at Ronnie's door, but the
 magnificent musicians he surrounded himself with. Guitarist Vivian Campbell
 was responsible for some of the crunchiest riffage this side of
 @{"Judas Priest" link "JUDAS PRIEST"}'s Glenn Tipton, and the powerful metal stance of albums
 such as 'Holy Diver' (1983) and 'The Last In Line' (1984), topped off
 by Ronnie's huge voice, are classics of the genre. Unfortunately, the
 mainman's constant dabbling with ludicrous fantasy lyrics and absurd
 stage shows (where he fought giant dragons!) made him look increasingly
 dated and he actually rejoined Black Sabbath for the dull 'Dehumanizer'
 album in 1992. Subsequent albums have been patchy at best, but his latest
 effort 'Magica' has been hailed as some sort of return to form.

 Recommended listening: 'Holy Diver'

