@node "EMP"

 ELP

 Or Emerson, Lake and Palmer - a trio of super-talented musos who came damn
 close to making the prog rock genre their own in the '70s. The band was
 a supergroup when it first formed: keyboard player Keith Emerson (ex-Nice),
 vocalist/bassist/guitarist Greg Lake (ex-King Crimson) and drummer Carl
 Palmer (ex-Atomic Rooster). And when they hit the 1970 Isle Of Wight
 Festival amid exploding cannons, a bombastic musical legend was born.
 Largely known for incorporating classical leanings into their overblown
 prog mayhem - all parping keyboards and seemingly endless compositions
 - large scale success came in the form of 1971's 'Tarkus', an unlikely and
 gloriously mad concept work about a battle between a manticore and a giant
 robot armadillo no, really! Just goes to show what crazy things you could
 get away with when immersing yourself in the heady waters of prog rock.
 More synthesisers and overwrought arrangements followed in its wake with
 the major success of 'Pictures At An Exhibition' and 'Trilogy'. 1977 saw
 the band enjoy one of their biggest hit singles in their inspired cover
 of Aaron Copeland's 'Fanfare For The Common Man'. With punk a burgeoning
 movement and their ill-advised attempt at a pop album (1978's 'Love
 Beach'), their success gradually began to wane and they split until a
 slight comeback in the early '90s where they performed three hugely
 successful shows at London's Royal Albert Hall and recorded 'Black Moon'
 (1992).

 Recommended listening: 'Tarkus'

@endnode


@node "EMPEROR"

 EMPEROR

 Purveyors of the blackest in black metal, Norway's Emperor were always
 guaranteed a place in metal's hall of infamy. Not only were the band -
 featuring long-standing founding member vocalist/guitarist/keyboardist
 Ihsahn - steeped in the traditions of thrash metal, but they brought
 a whole new dimension to the genre through a desire for musical innovation
 hitherto unconnected with metal. Not only was the music malevolently dark
 and blisteringly fast, but it featured a major interest in the brooding
 majesty of Norwegian folk music and the sombre shadings of classical
 traditions. The resulting gothic thunder enhanced the satanic horror of
 the lyrics to terrific effect, a sound which immediately garnered a major
 cult following upon the release of 1994's 'In The Nightside Eclipse' and
 which has subsequently been developed on 1997's 'Anthems To The Welkin At
 Dusk' and most recently, on 1999's 'IX Equilibrium'. Unfortunately, the
 band were not only noted for their musical experimentation, but also for
 their overtly anti-Christian sentiments, which spilled over into various
 criminal deeds, including acts of violence and arson on churches.
 The various members' apparent inability to rein in the worst excesses of
 violence eventually led to a fatal stabbing incident and the subsequent
 conviction of drummer Faust.

 Recommended Listening: 'In The Nightside Eclipse'

@endnode


@node "EUROPE"

 EUROPE

 Big hair and teeth - lots of shiny white teeth! - and girls swooning all
 over the front row. Yes, indeed, Europe singer Joey Tempest must be in the
 house. For a band that won a national rock competition in their native
 Sweden, they have come a very, very long way indeed. Officially formed
 in 1982, their prize was a recording contract and, boy, did they capitalise
 on the chance they'd been given. A self-titled debut was recorded and duly
 exploded into Sweden's Top 10. With an Epic record deal, 1985 brought
 'Wings Of Tomorrow', a sound- and image-friendly record. But it was
 1986 that saw their finest hour - well, four minutes or so, actually.
 'The Final Countdown' was yet another lush and smooth-sounding rock album,
 but nestling in its oh-so-wholesome grooves was the smash hit title track,
 featuring a huge drum sound and an even huger, parptastic keyboard refrain.
 And then, of course, there was the charismatically anodyne Joey Tempest
 and his lovely perm. In a pop rock climate that had catapulted @{"Bon Jovi" link "BON JOVI"}
 heavenward, how could such a soft-rocking gem fail? The album went triple
 platinum and then some. Sadly, with such meteoric success, the danger is
 of not being able to repeat the feat and Europe fell victim to it with
 respectable efforts in 'Out Of This World' and 'Prisoners In Paradise'.
 However, nothing could match the irritatingly catchy albatross around their
 collective necks.

 Recommended listening: 'The Final Countdown'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "EXTREME"

 EXTREME

 The success of Extreme in the early '90s can pretty much be attributed to
 the fantastically adept talents of guitarist Nuno Bettencourt. The initial
 line-up of the band had come together around 1985, with @{"Cheap Trick" link "CHEAP TRICK"} and
 @{"Queen" link "QUEEN"} pretensions to the fore, but were going nowhere until Bettencourt
 showed up in 1986 and 'Play With Me' ended up on the 'Bill And Ted's
 Excellent Adventure' soundtrack. With 1991's 'Pornograffitti', however,
 things began to take off with real momentum. 'Get The Funk Out' was a
 cheerfully cheeky @{"Red Hot Chili Peppers" link "RED HOT CHILI PEPPERS"} rip-off that smoothed off any
 rough edges to form a squeaky clean radio-friendly sound and killer chorus.
 It was with the super-smoochy ballad 'More Than Words', however, that their
 fate was sealed as MTV faves to mothers and daughters alike. In 1992, they
 wore their influences literally on their sleeves when they turned in a
 staggering performance at the Freddie Mercury Tribute concert at Wembley
 Stadium and then released 'III Sides To Every Story'. A new single 'Tragic
 Comic' was a less resounding hit and then things started to slide with
 'Waiting For The Punchline' (1995). Since then, lead vocalist Gary Cherone
 turned up as replacement to Sammy Hagar with Eddie and co. for '@{"Van Halen" link "VAN HALEN"}
 III' (1998) and hasn't done anything of note since. Neither, thinking
 about it, have the rest of the Extremists.

 Recommended listening: 'Pornograffitti'

