@node "FAITH NO MORE"

 FAITH NO MORE

 True originals are few and far between in the world of rock; some bands
 find their niche as fine imitators of their heroes, others pioneer a whole
 new sound and experience. Faith No More definitely fit into the latter
 category. Not many bands would dare to cover both Bee Gees and Dead
 Kennedys songs, dabble in death metal and funk, and still make it all
 sound seamless and natural. Formed in San Francisco in the early '80s,
 the original Chuck Moseley-fronted incarnation of the band came to
 prominence with the cataclysmically catchy funk rap of 'We Care A Lot',
 a rehashing of a tune from their eponymous 1985 debut. The ironically
 titled follow-up, 'Introduce Yourself', was just as much a peculiarly
 eclectic mish-mash of styles, as much a product of keyboardist Roddy
 Bottum's lush playing as, say, guitarist 'Big Sick Ugly' Jim Martin's
 penchant for @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"}. It was with a new singer, however - the
 scatalogically porn-fixated Mike Patton - that they truly blossomed.
 He could sing everything from rap to cod-metal opera, and the band simply
 erupted musically in all directions with the awesome commerciality of
 'The Real Thing', and the menacingly dark masterpiece 'Angel Dust'.
 The hit single cover version of the Commodores' 'I'm Easy' sealed their
 fate as one of the most perversely unique rock acts of the '90s, while
 'King For A Day - Fool for A Lifetime' and the diversely accomplished
 'Album Of The Year' kept defying expectations. In the end, though, the
 band fizzled out, due to lack of commitment from various members, leaving
 behind a highly original body of music and the tantalising possibilities
 of a reunion.

 Recommended listening: 'Angel Dust'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "FEAR FACTORY"

 FEAR FACTORY

 Call them cyber-metal, call them industrial metal, call them just plain
 old heavy metal - LA's Fear Factory are all these things and more, their
 innovative stance and sound going some way toward influencing the current
 crop of so called nu-metal bands. Formed in 1990, the aim behind Fear
 Factory was to take the basic sound of death metal and introduce the icy
 precision of industrial and electronic textures to counterpoint the band's
 enduring fascination with technology and man's relationship to it.
 Arguably, the main creative force lay with guitarist Dino Cazares and
 vocalist Burton C Bell, who put together both the brutal music and the
 chillingly bleak lyrics between them. The result of this unique artistic
 vision was 1992's 'Soul Of A New Machine', a pummeling and intense journey
 through some very dark musical noisescapes. In order to show that they were
 interested in the creative impetus provided by new technology, they allowed
 some of the tracks to be remixed for 1993's 'Fear Is The Mind Killer'. This
 experiment put them at the forefront of metal's crossover with less guitar
 based styles of music and encouraged other bands to be equally open-minded
 about their music. This pattern was repeated for 1995's 'Demanufacture',
 which was remixed into 'Remanufacture (Cloning Technology)' a couple of
 years later by a number of notable techno-oriented artists. Never ones to
 stretch themselves in terms of work rate, Fear Factory also found time to
 dabble with a number of side-projects before returning to their cyber
 manifesto with the conceptual sci-fi of 1999's 'Obsolete'.

 Recommended listening: 'Demanufacture'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "FILTER"

 FILTER

 It is virtually impossible to categorise the diverse and powerful sound of
 Filter, a fact that is all the more fascinating when one considers that the
 band is actually the vehicle for just one man to exercise his own unique
 artistic vision. Multi-instrumentalist and programmer Richard Patrick was
 originally a member of the touring incarnation of @{"Nine Inch Nails" link "NINE INCH NAILS"} back
 in the early 90s and as such was obviously immersed in the sounds of
 industrial and dance-based music, as well as the profound possibilities
 technology held for the aspiring musician. The first Filter record, 1995's
 'Short Bus', also featured the talents of a like-minded musical adventurer
 in Brian Liesegang. The remarkable thing about 'Short Bus' was that, true
 to the ethic that technology could free up creativity, it was recorded in
 a small house rather than an expensive studio, and its expansive
 soundscapes and energy are the direct product of just two people's musical
 imaginations. The record became a hit thanks to the alternative radio
 single 'Hey Man, Nice Shot' and, though Liesegang left in 1997, Patrick
 continued to pursue the Filter ethic with the mindstretching moods and
 textures of 'Title Of Record'.

 Recommended listening: 'Title Of Record'

@endnode


@node "FOO FIGHTERS"

 FOO FIGHTERS

 What the hell is a Foo Fighter? It's apparently the name given to
 mysterious UFO-like lights spotted by US air force pilots during World
 War II. And also the clever name adopted by ex-@{"Nirvana" link "NIRVANA"} drummer Dave Grohl
 for the outfit he formed in the wake of Kurt Cobain's suicide in early
 1994. Grohl had always nurtured a latent musical talent away from his
 customary drumkit, and a low-key example of his songwriting can be sampled
 as the b-side to Nirvana's penultimate single 'Heart Shaped Box'.
 'Marigold' may be unspectacular, but was indicative of a talent waiting
 to blossom, and blossom it did with the Foo Fighters' self-titled debut
 in 1995. Comparisons with his former band were inevitable, and some
 dismissed his work as Nirvana lite, but in its headlong rush of melodic
 power pop, it was so much more life-affirming than Nirvana's introspective
 musings. This was perfectly evident with the storming single 'This Is A
 Call', all blistering riffs, cryptic lyrics and a huge chorus. Follow-up
 album, 'The Colour And The Shape' (1997), proved that the first album had
 been no fluke. More of a band effort, rather than Grohl working through
 demos, the pop hardcore of the debut had metamorphosed into a diverse and
 immensely satisfying soundscape. Since then, Grohl has dabbled in several
 side-projects - composing music for films for some of the time - but the
 Foo Fighters returned in late 1999 with another powerful album, 'There
 Is Nothing Left To Lose'.

 Recommended listening: 'Foo Fighters'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "FOREIGNER"

 FOREIGNER

 If you want big ballads, then Foreigner are the band for you. But that
 really is only half the story, because this superlative bunch of musicians
 are not only responsible for getting those lighters waving and the radio
 playing in slick AOR fashion, they could also kick out some seriously
 belting rock tunes when the mood took them. Formed back in 1976, rock
 veteran guitarist Mick Jones recruited some seriously talented individuals
 in Ian McDonald (multi-instrumentalist), Dennis Elliott (drums),
 Ed Gagliardi (bass), Al Greenwood (keyboards), and last, but definitely
 not least, Lou Gramm (vocals). In Gramm, the band had a singer of immense
 skill and flexibility, the kind of larynx technician who could do justice
 to both the softest ballad and the grittiest rocker. So, following in the
 bluesy tradition of outfits such as @{"Bad Company" link "BAD COMPANY"}, the band took melody to
 their hearts and polished it to the point where radio stations the world
 over couldn't resist them. The late '70s brought hits both in the UK and
 the States, but it was always in America that they found their sound to be
 best appreciated. However, it was with production whizz Mutt Lange at the
 helm of 1981's '4' that the band went stratospheric. The hits flowed
 easily, most notably 'Waiting For a Girl Like You', a huge radio single.
 1984's 'Agent Provocateur' went seriously for the heavily keyboard-oriented
 rock sound of the mid '80s and spawned another mega-hit with 'I Want To
 Know What Love Is'. Love 'em or loathe 'em, you couldn't escape 'em!
 This was undoubtedly Foreigner's glory period and subsequent albums and
 incarnations of the band have been markedly less successful, with only a
 recent 'best of' album, featuring a few new songs, being of major interest.

 Recommended listening: '4'

@endnode


@node "FREE"

 FREE

 This stunning blues rock outfit may only have been in existence for five
 years, but during that time, they carved out a body of authentically
 passionate work that still sounds fresh and convincing today. Formed back
 in 1968, the classic line-up consisted of Paul Rodgers (vocals), Paul
 Kossoff (guitar), Andy Fraser (bass) and Simon Kirke (drums).
 Blues veteran Alexis Korner suggested they adopt the name Free and they
 wisely fended off an attempt by their label (Island) to rename them,
 believe it or not, The Heavy Metal Kids - a suggestion presumably down to
 the fact that they were still teenagers at the time. The late '60s rock
 scene was still heavily influenced by the blues and 1968's 'Tons Of Sobs'
 revelled in the sound, with Rodgers, in particular, developing a rich and
 soulful style. With the follow-up, 1969's 'Free', Rodgers and Fraser were
 becoming something of a writing superteam, and by the time of their third
 album, 1970's 'Fire And Water', they had come up with their most enduring
 song to date, the raw romp of 'All Right Now' - amazingly a UK hit five
 times in three different decades - making them household names the world
 over. The summer of 1970 saw them at the peak of their powers and playing
 to over half a million herbally relaxed punters at the Isle Of Wight
 Festival. As ever, the high couldn't last and internal friction was
 exacerbated by the relative failure of 'Highway', their second album
 of 1970. At this point, the band split and then reformed briefly in '72,
 but the magic was long gone.

 Recommended listening: 'Fire And Water'

