@node "GARBAGE"

 GARBAGE

 Comparisons with a more metallic Blondie were inevitable when Garbage
 first began to make an impression on the post-grunge, post-Nirvana music
 scene. After all, here was an attractive young lady, in the form of
 Shirley Manson, fronting what was essentially a heavied up pop act.
 But in reality, the outfit was the brainchild of @{"The Smashing Pumpkins" link "THE SMASHING PUMPKINS"},
 Sonic Youth and @{"Nirvana" link "NIRVANA"} producer Butch Vig and a couple of other
 knob-twiddling cohorts who were fed up by their behind-the-desk personas
 and wanted some more attention-grabbing action. Having already suffered
 a number of false starts with various groups over the preceding years,
 finding Manson was a blessing, because she would become the focus of the
 group, bringing all manner of dark, brooding facets to the band's sound
 and direction. When the band's first self-titled album appeared in 1995,
 their success inevitably had critics reaching for the N-word. 'Garbage',
 however, was a lot more than old formulas rehashed - it had a gothic,
 industrial flavour to the all-pervading angst, more of a @{"Nine Inch Nails" link "NINE INCH NAILS"}
 than a Nirvana. Most importantly, it spawned a number of hits, thanks to
 the clever pop production values. The single that truly broke the band was
 the cheerfully miserable 'Only Happy When It Rains', with Manson doing
 a fine look-at-wretched-little-me act, a ploy that worked very well on
 follow-up single, 'Stupid Girl'. With new album 'Version 2.0' (1998),
 Garbage have proved that they can still crank out the hits and please
 the fans with yet another slice of neo-goth pop.

 Recommended listening: 'Garbage'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "GARY MOORE"

 GARY MOORE

 A prickly though well-respected and hugely talented guitarist, Moore has
 most recently been working through a period of his career that has seen him
 concentrating on the blues. This aspect of his career, well-represented on
 the likes of early 90s albums 'Still Got The Blues' and 'After Hours', he
 is still best loved in the far heavier incarnation from his early years.
 Moore's career first took off with @{"Skid Row" link "SKID ROW"}, not Bon Jovi's pet project
 featuring Seb Bach, but the Irish band with more traditional rock roots.
 He recorded two albums with them ('70's 'Skid' and '71's '34 Hours')
 before a solo effort, 1973's 'Grinding Stone'. His real leap into the
 limelight came, however, when he joined Phil Lynott and @{"Thin Lizzy" link "THIN LIZZY"} - he
 was with the band for only a few months in 1974 before truly making his
 name on the Lizzy classic, 1979's 'Black Rose'. One of the band's finest
 records it was a superb showcase for Moore's mercurial lead work, but
 being an uncompromising musician he jumped ship just as real fame
 threatened. Lizzy proved to be a perfect springboard into his most
 metallic and enjoyable period of the early 80s. 'Back On The Streets'
 gave him his famous signature track of 'Parisienne Walkways' before the
 likes of 'Corridors Of Power' and 'Victims Of The Future' made him a major
 influential rock attraction in his own right. This period of 80s success
 was sealed with a storming UK Top Five single hit with 1985's 'Out In The
 Fields', a song performed alongside Lizzy's Phil Lynott. Finally, with
 a couple of less well-received Big Country style LPs behind him, Moore
 finally entered his long lasting bluesman phase.

 Recommended listening: 'Victims Of The Future'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Still Got the Blues'

@endnode


@node "GEORGIA SATELLITES"

 GEORGIA SATELLITES

 The success of this wonderfully unpretentious bunch of southern boogie
 merchants can almost certainly be attributed to the cheerfully raucous
 songwriting talents of guitarist Dan Baird. Here was a man who could
 make the simplest chord sing and cheekiest lyric trip off the tongue
 like poetry. A low-key debut, 'Keep The Faith' (1985), was just the
 beginning for what would prove to be a fun, if short-lived, reign as
 rock stars. As a mere taster of their good, old-fashioned blues 'n'
 boogie approach to songwriting, 'Keep The Faith' was fine, but it was
 the major hit single 'Keep Your Hands To Yourself', with its lazily
 drawled vocals and charming swagger that put them and their eponymous
 1986 album at the top of the heap. Here was a band not afraid to mimic
 the greats and liberal splashes of the Rolling Stones and Faces peppered
 the record; they even covered Rod Stewart's 'Every Picture Tells A Story'.
 Follow-up albums, 'Open All Night' and 'In The Land Of Salvation And Sin',
 followed pretty much the same blueprint, but neither of them could capture
 the same spark of interest, and Baird eventually quit the band to pursue
 a solo career.

 Recommended listening: 'Georgia Satellites'

@endnode


@node "GIRLSCHOOL"

 GIRLSCHOOL

 Few all-female rock bands are spoken of with quite such high regard as
 South London's Girlschool, a powerhouse of grinding guitars and staunchly
 gutsy attitude. Formed back in 1977 as the dodgily monikered Painted Lady,
 their classic line-up consisted of Kim McAuliffe (guitar/vocals), Enid
 Williams (bass/vocals), Kelly Johnson (lead guitar/vocals) and Denise
 Dufort (drums) and with their brash biker metal sound, they set about
 convincing the macho world of rock that the girls could be just as tough
 as the boys. Famously, @{"Motorhead" link "MOTORHEAD"}'s Lemmy championed the band early on,
 helping them sign to Bronze Records and allowing them a support slot on
 an early Motorhead tour. Not that they necessarily needed the favours,
 because early albums such as 'Demolition' and 'Hit & Run' were speedy
 raucous albums of solid and powerful hard rock. The band's most memorable
 period, however, is doubtless their tongue-in-cheek collaboration with
 Motorhead for 1982's 'The St Valentine's Day Massacre' EP, which resulted
 in the two outfits covering each other's songs and playing the old Johnny
 Kidd classic 'Please Don't Touch' on 'Top Of The Pops'. This period is
 often looked upon with great affection, because thereafter a series of
 personnel shifts and a general feeling of disillusionment began to colour
 subsequent releases. Though the band continue to this day - they apparently
 have a record in the works right now - playing the occasional gig and
 releasing the odd album, they don't have the same rampant momentum behind
 them.

 Recommended listening: 'Demolition'

@endnode


@node "GREAT WHITE"

 GREAT WHITE

 Named after a shark known for taking the odd bite out of human flesh, you'd
 have expected Great White to perhaps be a little more aggressive than they
 actually were. Formed around 1982, this LA bar band quickly notched up
 a reputation for hard-rocking blues, a style no doubt developed from long
 and hard study of the @{"Led Zeppelin" link "LED ZEPPELIN"} and Rolling Stones songbook. And with
 frontman Jack Russell a past master at whipping up a crowd, they were
 a superb good-time party outfit. Their debut was the Don Dokken-produced
 'Out Of The Night' EP, which got them a deal with EMI, but resulted in
 a poorly received debut album in 1984, and their subsequent split from
 the label. Their next EP, 'Shot In The Dark', is regarded as one of their
 finest and the album that came after it, 1987's 'Once Bitten...',
 is something of a minor classic, featuring a brace of highly melodic but
 rough 'n' ready belters, with Russell sounding particularly powerful.
 Subsequent recordings have been patchy, but the band clearly know where
 their strengths lie, and 'Recovery...Live' (1988) effectively captured
 the band at their best - that is, in a live context. The band continue
 to record and tour and recently released their first studio effort of the
 new millennium, entitled 'Can't Get There From Here', featuring yet more
 writing input from Don Dokken.

 Recommended listening: 'Once Bitten...'

@endnode


@node "GREEN DAY"

 GREEN DAY

 This cheerful Californian trio can pretty much lay claim to having created
 the present pop punk format so carelessly thrashed around by so many bands
 these days. Forming back in Berkeley in 1990, the band originally traded
 under the unlikely named of the Sweet Children before they adopted their
 equally unlikely present name. Their first album, '39/Smooth', was
 completed, amazingly, in just one day and started them off on the road to
 three-chord punk heaven. By the time of 'Kerplunk' (1992), the so-called
 classic line-up of original members Billy Joe Armstrong (guitar/nasal
 vocals), Mike Dirnt (bass/slightly less nasal vocals) and new drummer
 Tre Cool (aka Frank Edwin Wright III) was in place. At this point, the
 band really began to borrow all the best bits from their punk forefathers.
 Their sound was unashamedly bright and poppy, but contained sufficient bite
 to be cool - a formula which went a major way to making 'Dookie' (1994) one
 of the most consistently enjoyable rock records of the '90s. The songs
 betrayed a touch of teenage angst here, a little sensitivity there, but the
 emphasis was on fun throughout. It was simple stuff and over 10 million
 people thought it was fantastic enough to buy! Having established the
 commercial credibility of the genre subsequent albums, 'Insomniac' and
 'Nimrod' have trodden the same path with just a little more diversity in
 the songwriting.

 Recommended listening: 'Dookie'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "GUNS N' ROSES"

 GUNS N' ROSES

 Few bands have the reputation of being genuinely dangerous - the Gunners
 are a band who earned the accolade with ease and no uncertain relish.
 Emerging from the LA sleaze scene in the mid '80s, Axl Rose (vocals),
 Slash (guitar), Izzy Stradlin' (guitar), Duff McKagan (bass) and Steven
 Adler (drums) enjoyed something of a bad boy reputation, even before they
 set foot in a studio. These guys almost literally lived on the street and
 did whatever they could to survive. Their suitably tacky 1986 debut
 'Live ?!*@ Like A Suicide' gave some indication of their worth, but it was
 with the unparalleled toxic charm of 'Appetite For Destruction' that the
 monster was truly spawned. This was rock 'n' roll at a visceral level.
 Ripping off the best moves from a number of obvious influences, ranging
 from the @{"Sex Pistols" link "SEX PISTOLS"} to @{"Aerosmith" link "AEROSMITH"}, 'Appetite...' gave them a string of
 hits ('Welcome To The Jungle', 'Paradise City', 'Sweet Child O' Mine')
 and let the band loose to trash hotel rooms and cause riots the world
 over, with Axl and his rampaging rock star ego leading from the front.
 They courted controversy with the semi-acoustic 'G N' R Lies' and its
 apparent attacks on ethnic minorities and homosexuals (the infamous
 'One In A Million'), and inevitable line-up changes due to drugs (natch).
 Come the early '90s, and with a massive world tour behind them, they
 returned with the monumental blow-out that was 'Use Your Illusion I & II',
 a bloated two-part epic - their attempt to make a 'Physical Graffiti'.
 Another massive bout of touring and an album of cover versions
 ('The Spaghetti Incident') later, and the band began to disintegrate,
 until only Axl and his ego were left along with a collection of hired
 hands. Despite the loss of most of the original line-up and a less than
 impressive work rate, a new album titled 'The Chinese Democracy' is
 expected in summer 2000.

 Recommended listening: 'Appetite For Destruction'

