@node "HANOI ROCKS"

 HANOI ROCKS

 It's strange to think that one of the bands to follow on from the '70s
 legacy left by the likes of the New York Dolls would hail from Finland,
 but that's exactly where this bunch of hard-living maniacs called home.
 Formed back in 1980 and fronted by the androgynously charming Michael
 Monroe and his finely honed cheek bones, this ramshackle glam punk outfit
 pinched all the best bits from Bowie, the Stones, the New York Dolls -
 hell, the list is almost inexhaustible! - and splurged it out in a sleazy
 style which has since found favour with the likes of Backyard Babies and
 the Hellacopters, among other modern Scandinavian rock types. Their trash
 ethic was bound to make them stars if the likes of 'Back To Mystery City'
 (1983) and 'Two Steps From The Move' (1984) were anything to go by, were
 it not for the tragic fate that befell their drummer, Razzle.
 While touring the US in 1984, Razzle took an ill-advised car ride with
 a drunken Vince Neil, singer of @{"Motley Crue" link "MOTLEY CRUE"}, and the resulting car smash
 cost him his life. Hanoi were devastated and though they managed to
 continue for a short while afterward, the shock was too great and they
 eventually split.

 Recommended listening: 'Back To Mystery City'

@endnode


@node "HEART"

 HEART

 The story of sisters Ann and Nancy Wilson is basically one of dedication
 and an almost unbelievable degree of self-belief. Heart started off in
 1974 as an essentially folky outfit. Not that they sang with one finger
 jammed in their ears, but their @{"Led Zeppelin" link "LED ZEPPELIN"}-inspired brand of rock was
 tempered by a gentle, whimsical nature. It was a rich mixture of influences
 and while Nancy was a superb guitarist, Ann's vocals were soaringly
 powerful. This early period for the band was characterised by debut album
 'Dreamboat Annie' and singles such as 'Crazy About You' and 'Magic Man',
 both US Top 40 hits. 1979's 'Dog And Butterfly' album was, perhaps, their
 most successful at capturing the complexities of melody and powerful
 guitarwork. Come the early '80s, however, and with serious personnel and
 legal problems dogging the band, they found themselves reduced to a duo
 and in desperate need of reinvention. At this career nadir, a new Heart
 was born, with a little help from MTV and a couple of superlative soft
 rock albums. Their eponymous 1985 album contained major hits 'What About
 Love?' and 'These Dreams', and 1987's 'Bad Animals' contained such smashes
 as 'Alone' and 'Never'. 1990's 'Brigade' did more of the same, and the
 plush soft rock template Heart stamped with their own inimitable identity
 proved to be their most enduring incarnation.

 Recommended listening: 'Bad Animals'

@endnode


@node "HELLOWEEN"

 HELLOWEEN

 German five-piece Helloween were always a little bit strange. When the rest
 of the thrash scene were busy riffing like demons and festooning their
 cover artwork with gore and skulls, they went for a sort of chirpy-style
 speed metal and, um, smiley pumpkins. Presumably in an effort to ape
 @{"Iron Maiden" link "IRON MAIDEN"}, Helloween adopted Pumpkinhead as a mascot and proceeded
 to borrow some of Maiden's galloping twin-guitar style too.
 First album 'Walls Of Jericho' was a tough-sounding speedfest, but they
 soon polished off the rough edges and streamlined the speed to conjure
 up the magnificently overblown 'Keeper Of The Seven Keys Part I'.
 The guitars were devastatingly precise and thunderously heavy, with the
 songs addressing everything from the nuclear arms race to the full-blown
 epic fantasy title track. And all the way through, there ran a weird
 streak of whimsical Teutonic humour. The follow-up, 1988's imaginatively
 titled 'Keeper Of The Seven Keys Part II', was more of the same, and the
 band won the opening slot at the Donington Monsters Of Rock Festival on the
 back of their 'Dr Stein' single. Following their initial run of success,
 however, key guitar genius Kai Hansen departed to form Gamma Ray, and the
 band lost momentum with 'Pink Bubbles Go Ape' and 'Chameleon'.
 Most recently, they have dabbled with a bunch of disparate cover versions
 on the decidedly odd 'Metal Jukebox' - presumably more of that German
 sense of humour shining through.

 Recommended listening: 'Keeper Of The Seven Keys Part I.'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

