@node "HELMET"

 HELMET

 Sometimes inappropriately lumped in with the grunge scene, New York's
 Helmet absolutely refused to have anything to do with the nascent grunge
 scene when they first formed back in 1989. They were less about jeans and
 flannel shirts and more about the disciplined intensity of noise.
 They began life in typical cult indie style by releasing a bunch of tough
 singles and EPs on the Amphetamine Reptile label and though their guitar
 violence shared some of the appeal of grunge for them, this was more by
 accident than design. Their aim was to keep arrangements to a minimum,
 thus exploring the true head-removing power of a single solid and violent
 riff, a blueprint followed to staggering effect with 1990's 'Strap It On'
 - a mean, pummeling record of primal garage mayhem. 1992's 'Meantime'
 found them dabbling with Steve Albini and his militantly raw recording
 values in the studio, and 1994's 'Betty' was really about as experimental
 as they would ever get. That is, not very. Around this time, the band were
 arguably at their commercial peak and recorded songs for inclusion on the
 soundtracks to 'Judgment Night' ('Just Another Victim' with House Of Pain)
 and 'The Crow' ('Milquetoast' recorded by production whizz Butch Vig).
 By the time of 'Aftertaste' (1997), they were back doing what they knew
 best - unleashing succinct chunks of ear-bleeding noise with an almost
 careless disregard for public safety.

 Recommended listening: 'Strap It On'

@endnode


@node "HENRY ROLLINS"

 HENRY ROLLINS

 Henry Rollins is without doubt one of the most industrious artists
 currently working on the music scene. He has several books to his name
 (under his own publishing imprint), he is an actor, an accomplished spoken
 word show veteran and also one of the most intense recording artists to
 ever commit noise to tape. Henry's recording career began when he joined
 highly influential hardcore band Black Flag in 1981. He stayed with the
 band for five years and became their longest serving singer, all the while
 developing the manic persona that would become his trademark over the
 ensuing years. By 1986, he felt the time was right to go solo and he put
 a band together to record 1987's 'Hot Animal Machine'. It was raw and
 energetic, but vast improvements would be made to the hard 'n' heavy blues
 based rock sound Henry wanted to experiment with. 'Life Time', 'Do It'
 and 'Hard Volume' went some way to realising Henry's goal with tighter
 production values, but it was the start of the '90s that really catapulted
 Rollins into the limelight. The band landed the opening slot for the
 Lollapalooza tour of 1991, bringing them nationwide exposure, and for the
 first time mainstream rock fans could experience the full-scale breezeblock
 intensity of Rollins giving his all in performance. His career was almost
 cut short later the same year when he and friend Joe Cole were caught in
 a mugging; his friend was killed, but rather than take a break as any
 normal individual would to recover, Rollins worked through his emotions on
 tour. Both 'The End Of Silence' (1992) and 'Weight' (1994) were incredibly
 tough albums, exceeded only by his latest vein-bulging slabs of lyrical
 catharsis, 1997's 'Come In And Burn' and the classic hard rock influences
 of 2000's 'Get Some Go Again'.

 Recommended listening: 'Get Some Go Again'

@endnode


@node "HOLE"

 HOLE

 Hole's leading primal force, the often difficult and downright scary
 Courtney Love, has been many things in her life - an exotic dancer, an
 actress, but most successfully, the captain of one of grunge's most
 successful female-fronted groups. Hole actually began life in Los Angeles
 in 1989, but it was with a move to Seattle and the release of a couple of
 singles on the supercool Sub Pop label that Hole really began to take off.
 Their first album, 1991's 'Pretty On The Inside', was an uncompromising
 and raw collection of feminine angst, betraying at turns an aching
 vulnerability and a screeching harridan fury. It ripped and shredded with
 an unrestrained, but hugely appealing, sense of anger and loss, not least
 because of Love's lyrical phrasing which came damn close to a kind of
 barbed poetry. This style put her in the same creative arena as @{"Nirvana" link "NIRVANA"}
 and in 1992, she famously married Kurt Cobain, with whom she had a child,
 Francis Bean. 1994's 'Live Through This' found the Hole sound adopting
 more poise and melody, but the huge creative progressions were somewhat
 swamped by Cobain's suicide in the same year. A mere two months later
 Hole's bassist, Kristen Pfaff, died of a heroin overdose. Since then,
 Hole's output has been as erratic as Love's volatile temperament and
 a series of stopgap releases allowed her to indulge in acting once more
 and to begin making in-roads into modelling. Hole's most recent album
 'Celebrity Skin', however, proved that they were still a major musical
 force when it was released in 1998.

 Recommended listening: 'Live Through This'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

