@node "JANE'S ADDICTION"

 JANE'S ADDICTION

 Art and rock aren't usually linked in an equal relationship, but with
 Jane's Addiction singer Perry Farrell, the link was not only natural,
 but absolutely essential to the creation of a musically unique entity.
 Early live show experiences of the band were, by all accounts, like
 visiting some sort of nightmarish freakshow, an atmosphere readily evident
 on their self-financed eponymous live debut. Their wilfully perverse and
 skewed rock vision found its most fully realised conduit in 1988's
 magnificently strange, but superbly hard-rocking, 'Nothing's Shocking'.
 Still considered their finest album, its blend of thrash, punk, rock and
 funk seemed to taunt the closed-minded. The heady psychedelic barrage was
 led by Perry's shrill and surreal vocals and guitarist Dave Navarro's
 scorching six-string talents. The songs were about sex, romance, death,
 sex, power and, er, sex. Furthermore, the cover featured a Farrell
 constructed sculpture of naked Siamese twins with their heads on fire.
 The result? Instant notoriety and the album being sold in a tastefully
 ribbed rubber sleeve. A similar fate befell the superb follow-up, 'Ritual
 De Lo Habitual', again with a sleeve guaranteed to have the self-appointed
 moral guardians howling for rock star blood. It was sold in some places in
 a plain white sleeve with the US constitution's First Amendment printed on
 it. Again, musically, it was incredibly astute and dazzling with the
 stand-out cut being the staggering ten minute rush of 'Three Days'.
 Sadly, with such thoroughly intense and volatile characters in the band,
 things soon disintegrated in a very public and extremely rock 'n' roll
 fashion, with Farrell and Navarro exchanging punches on the Lollapalooza
 festival stage.

 Recommended listening: 'Nothing's Shocking'

@endnode


@node "JETHRO TULL"

 JETHRO TULL

 Naming your band after an eighteenth century agriculturalist may not
 seem like the most sensible thing to do when forming a rock group, but then
 Jethro Tull were no ordinary band, preferring to indulge their own creative
 whims than to pander to what other people expected of them. Starting out
 as a blues outfit in 1967, their initial line-up was somewhat fluid, as
 the band began to establish a musical direction for themselves. The result
 of the first few years' toil was a move into progressive folk rock, a genre
 that Tull would soon make their own, mainly due to the single-minded
 creativity of songwriter Ian Anderson. A self-taught flautist and lyricist,
 he was arguably the band's visual focus as, wearing a prominent cod-piece,
 he took to histrionic flute-playing live, while often standing
 flamingo-like on one leg. As for the music, it may have been folky,
 but there was nothing fey about it, as Anderson's barbed and satirical
 lyrics were stinging in their accuracy and candour. The early '70s was
 arguably their creative peak and albums such as 'Stand Up', 'Benefit',
 but most famously 1971's 'Aqualung', featured innovative arrangements and
 a peculiarly English wit. The latter record, in particular, was a fine
 concept piece detailing the story of a tramp. Subsequent albums found the
 band adopting all sorts of concept ideas to varying degrees of critical
 success, but by the time of punk, they were looking decidedly wrong-footed
 as their style of rock became rapidly unfashionable. However, never ones
 to care much about fashion, the band have continued to release albums and
 tour successfully to this day.

 Recommended listening: 'Aqualung'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

