@node "JOE SATRIANI"

 JOE SATRIANI

 A truly influential and innovative technician Satriani's incredible skill
 with the guitar has seen him play in various rock outfits before launching
 a successful solo career in the mid 80s. His amazing technique and prowess
 originally found Satriani teaching the likes of @{"Steve Vai" link "STEVE VAI"} and @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"}'s
 Kirk Hammett among many lesser known six stringers, but his first foray
 into solo recording came with an eponymous EP in 1985. It was with the
 albums 'Not Of This Earth' and 'Surfing With The Alien', however, that
 Satriani really made headway as a solo artist. He was capable of
 encompassing many different styles - often within the space of a single
 composition - and with various tunes he also displayed a sly sense of
 humour, a very tricky quality to express through the six strings of
 a guitar. 1989's 'Flying In A Blue Dream' was the record that truly broke
 his talents on both sides of the Atlantic and actually featured the man's
 vocal talents as well. Despite this departure from the established pattern
 the album proved to be a major showcase for his talents and the singles
 'Big Bad Moon' and 'I Believe' even received attention from MTV. This was
 the main period of Satriani's success and, even though he continued with
 his solo output, led to him guesting on various albums including
 @{"Alice Cooper" link "ALICE COOPER"}'s 'Hey Stoopid' and even rock spoofers Spinal Tap's 'Break
 Like The Wind'.

 Recommended listening: 'Flying In A Blue Dream'

