@node "JOURNEY"

 JOURNEY

 For a band that epitomised the lush and melodic sound of FM radio in the
 '80s' San Francisco's Journey began life as something very scary indeed:
 jazz fusionists. Originally put together by guitar genius Neal Schon,
 who had played in Carlos Santana's band way back in 1972 the band
 unsurprisingly struggled to make a name for themselves and were actually
 threatened by their record label to get a singer or be dropped! With the
 arrival of phenomenal vocalist Steve Perry in 1977, they began to develop
 their smooth melodic hard rock sound with albums like 'Infinity',
 'Evolution', and 'Departure'. By the early '80s, they were already
 a platinum-selling act, following, essentially, in the melodic rock
 footsteps of pioneers such as @{"Free" link "FREE"} and @{"Bad Company" link "BAD COMPANY"}. However, with the
 addition of excellent keyboardist/guitarist Jonathan Cain, the Journey
 sound suddenly became massively successful. His songwriting boost gave
 them their all-time classic album in 1981's 'Escape', from beginning to
 end a polished AOR masterpiece; the sound of American radio rock had been
 officially established. 1986's 'Raised On Radio' repeated the mega-selling
 trick, and Journey went into the history books as one of the biggest,
 boldest and most melodic of rock bands ever. Period. Since then, the band
 has split, reformed and undergone some major personnel shifts, but they
 could never again quite capture the all-encompassing power of the mid-'80s
 incarnation.

 Recommended listening: 'Escape'

