 JUDAS PRIEST

 During the ludicrously big-haired '80s, there was pretty much only one band
 that was genuinely synonymous with the term 'heavy metal' - indeed, if
 Black Sabbath came up with the sound in the '70s, then these guys created
 the image to go with the racket - yet another outfit from Birmingham, the
 incomparable Judas Priest. Formed way back in 1969, it took up to the mid
 '70s for them to hit their stride and turn out a series of genre-defining
 rock albums, including 'British Steel' and 'Killing Machine' (dubbed 'Hell
 Bent For Leather' in the US, for obvious reasons). They will also be
 forever associated with the hardest studs-and-chains image this side
 of @{"Manowar" link "MANOWAR"}, with lead singer Rob Halford being one of the worst culprits
 when it came to leather and whips. Naturally, a string of gloriously
 over-the-top albums accompanied such absurd sartorial excesses' with the
 '80s releases 'Screaming For Vengeance', 'Defenders Of The Faith' and
 'Turbo' making them one of the biggest metal acts and the epitome of
 Satanic evil the world over. Which, of course, made them required
 listening for any right-minded teenager. Unfortunately, however, grunge
 changed the musical climate in the early '90s and with it, Halford
 departed for a solo career. After a quiet period, the band returned in the
 late '90s with a new singer - Tim 'Ripper' Owens - more than capable of
 handling material made unique through Halford's inimitable style, and
 continued to forge ahead with the brutal 'Jugulator' album.

 Recommended listening: 'Screaming For Vengeance'

