@node "KISS"

 KISS

 Surely one of the loudest, glammiest, trashiest rock bands ever to
 (dis)grace a stage, Kiss are the archetypal glitzy stadium band, the direct
 result of masterminds guitarist Paul Stanley and bassist Gene Simmons'
 desire to create a mythical rock legend in the mould of the Beatles:
 a gargantuan outfit with four distinct personalities making up the ranks,
 providing ample marketing opportunities for merchandising in the process!
 Formed back in 1972, it took the addition of guitarist Ace Frehley, drummer
 Pete Criss and a ton of greasepaint to launch Kiss in the guise most people
 revere them in. Since their spectacular rise in the States in the mid '70s,
 the band have gone through various line-up changes and recorded a fair few
 dodgy albums in their attempts to stay ahead of their public's fickle
 tastes, but it is for their initial period of success that they will
 forever be lauded. Starting with their 1974 self-titled debut, Kiss were
 rock gods of the decade, singing about girls, sex, rock 'n' roll,
 and more sex in a salacious and theatrical style that left nothing to the
 imagination - this was heavy metal turned into a Las Vegas cartoon.
 Their stage shows became the stuff of legend, what with the fire-breathing
 and various other cheesy stunts. 'Hotter Than Hell', 'Dressed To Kill',
 'Alive!' 'Destroyer' - hell, pick just about any of their mid '70s
 catalogue to experience huge riffs and ridiculously catchy choruses
 celebrating rock hedonism. Come the late '70s and punk, however, and it
 all started to go wrong as each member individually released a solo album
 which stiffed. The early '80s weren't much better and the band decided to
 'unmask' themselves. By the late '80s, with their popularity waning once
 more, the band decided that what the '90s needed was greasepaint again.
 Hence, for the last few years, Kiss have enjoyed something of a resurgence
 in fortune, especially with the release of 'Psycho Circus', an album
 praised as being a return to the magic Kiss formula of the '70s.

 Recommended listening: 'Destroyer'

@endnode


@node "KORN"

 KORN

 Progenitors of nu-metal, this relatively young Californian outfit have been
 at the forefront of the latest rock trend to sweep through the world of
 rock music. Formed back in 1993 by the amalgamation of local Californian
 outfit LAPD's musical core with Sexart singer Jonathan Davis, Korn were
 unique right from their inception. In Davis, they had a singer not afraid
 to recount the most harrowing and unsavoury of episodes from his personal
 and family life, and his style would often range from outright shrieking
 to a machine-gun rattle of rap and rage. The lyrical angst was augmented
 by a brutal, downtuned sludge style of metal, with Davis also pitching in
 with hideous squalls of bagpipe noise! For some reason, this rhythmic style
 was unimaginatively dubbed 'funk metal' at first, but by the time of Korn's
 first self-titled album in 1994, it was quite clear they had forged a
 unique sound for the '90s which incorporated the coolness of hip-hop with
 the thunder of powerful rock. Not only that, but they were uniquely aware
 of their street level appeal, and they adopted their now-ubiquitous sports
 wear theme. Follow-up album 'Life Is Peachy' sounded even more painfully
 intense than the debut and by the time of 'Follow The Leader' in 1998,
 the band had become fully fledged MTV rock stars at the top of the metal
 scene, both in terms of sound and commercial style.

 Recommended listening: 'Follow The Leader'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Korn'

