@node "KYUSS"

 KYUSS

 Some bands are simply not destined to survive their initial formative
 throes, but few of them actually manage to make a vital and critical mark
 on the scene over such a short life span. Hailing from the desert area of
 Southern California, Kyuss were just such a band. Formed back in the very
 early '90s by guitarist Josh Homme, vocalist John Garcia, bassist Nick
 Oliveri and drummer Brant Bjork, they made name for themselves in their
 local area as a ferocious live act. Their first album, 1991's 'Wretch',
 failed to capture their sound, but they did grab the attention of Chris
 Goss, singer/guitarist of Masters Of Reality. He had been attracted by
 Kyuss' organic shaping of that classic '70s rock sound, the fuzzy riffage
 of Blue Cheer, the doomy melancholy of @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"} and those distinct
 undercurrents of barely restrained psychedelia. The album he produced with
 them would become the benchmark by which 'stoner' rock would be judged in
 the '90s. 'Blues For The Red Sun' was superbly heavy and strikingly
 innovative, even though it recycled the standards of the past. Sadly,
 even as the stoner phenomenon had found its stylistic template, Kyuss
 began to fall apart after the monumental 'Sky Valley' album. 'And The
 Circus Leaves Town' suffered from being produced by a band in its death
 throes and with that, they all split to form various similar outfits such
 as Queens Of The Stone Age and Unida.

 Recommended listening: 'Blues For The Red Sun'

