@node "LED ZEPPELIN"

 LED ZEPPELIN

 Formed by The Yardbirds' guitarist Jimmy Page in 1968, Led Zeppelin
 originally rejoiced under the clever name The New Yardbirds until Who
 drummer, the irrepressible Keith Moon suggested they were 'so heavy they
 should go down like a lead zeppelin'. Whatever the genesis of the name,
 it would have meant nothing had the music been less than magnificent.
 At first using a heavy blues approach the band's sound developed rapidly
 during the '70s to incorporate everything from funk to reggae, and with
 it - under the guidance of manager Peter Grant, often dubbed the fifth
 member - their stature grew as they became one of the biggest, most
 outrageous acts in the world, a name synonymous with rock star excess.
 Not only was their lifestyle flamboyant but the albums became ever more
 ambitious and lavish. Most famous for the mystical classic 'Stairway To
 Heaven' on the gloriously diverse 'Led Zeppelin IV', their expansive and
 overtly experimental approach is best captured on the monumental,
 fantastically overblown double album extravaganza 'Physical Graffiti' in
 1975. Despite the obviously rock dinosaur-culling power of the '70s punk
 explosion what actually destroyed the band was the sudden death of drummer
 John Bonham in 1980, after a drinking binge at Page's house.

 Recommended listening: (missing)

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Led Zeppelin IV.'

