@node "LIMP BIZKIT"

 LIMP BIZKIT

 Yet another band somewhat loosely lumped in with the fresh nu-metal
 phenomenon, there's really a lot more to the Limp Bizkit game plan than
 simple angst and a penchant for gut-churning, downtuned guitars.
 Somewhat bizarrely, the band began life in that haven of southern rock,
 Jacksonville, Florida. There was nothing even remotely 'southern' about
 the style of music vocalist Fred Durst and bassist Sam Rivers were
 interested in making, however. Theirs was a uniquely '90s brand of rock,
 suffused with the street cred of hip-hop and the punk attitude of grunge.
 Most importantly they knew how to deliver with intensity. Famously,
 post-gig, Korn's bassist Fieldy and guitarist Head found themselves in
 Durst's tattoo parlour, where the ambitious frontman befriended them,
 and they passed his band demo tape on to legendary metal producer Ross
 Robinson. Hence support slots with the likes of House Of Pain resulted
 and when those hip-hoppers called it a day, the Bizkit grabbed their
 DJ Lethal. The Limp Bizkit picture was now complete. With DJ Lethal
 providing a vibey, infectious groove by using his turntable skills like
 another instrument, it was just a matter of time before this modern
 rock-rap hybrid caught the attention of the MTV generation. 1997's 'Three
 Dollar Bill Y'All$' was a major hit. By the time of 1999's follow-up,
 'Significant Other', Durst was fulfilling his ambitions to become
 a major influence in the world of entertainment, and the album, as
 a result, features a plethora of big name performers, ranging fro
 @{"Stone Temple Pilots" link "STONE TEMPLE PILOTS"}' Scott Weiland and Korn's Jonathan Davis to
 Wu Tang Clan's Method Man.

 Recommended listening: 'Significant Other'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

