@node "LITA FORD"

 LITA FORD

 When all-girl band @{"The Runaways" link "THE RUNAWAYS"} crashed and burned at the end of the 70s
 only two of the members went on to anything resembling stardom. One was,
 of course, Joan Jett (with her Blackhearts) and the other was blonde
 bombshell Lita Ford. Ford had actually started to learn the guitar at the
 tender age of eleven, so by the time of the early 80s all she had to do
 was develop her singing voice in order to launch a solo career.
 The direction she took was slightly removed from the punky glam bad-girl
 rock of her previous outfit, however. For the 80s a more streamlined sound
 was de rigeur, but 1983's 'Out For Blood' album was, nevertheless, a fine
 showcase for her guitar talents, proving that when it came to rock she
 could play as tough as any man. Despite this obvious success the 80s
 proved to be rather patchy and she eventually went on to record
 'The Bride Wore Black' for RCA, a record that was never released.
 Towards the end of the decade, however, rock had found a mainstream
 presence in the pop charts and 1988's 'Lita' was her biggest and most
 successful album containing hit singles in both 'Kiss Me Deadly' and her
 famed duet with @{"Ozzy Osbourne" link "OZZY OSBOURNE"} 'Close My Eyes Forever'. The latter gave
 both artists their first ever US Top Ten hit. For some reason best known
 to Ford she then went on to marry @{"WASP" link "WASP"} wild man Chris Holmes before
 realising the error of her ways, and as an artist suffered greatly in the
 grunge explosion of the early 90s.

 Recommended listening: 'Lita'

@endnode


@node "LIVE"

 LIVE

 Just as punk brought a few really innovative and influential outfits to
 the fore in the 70s so grunge brought a few worthwhile bands to prominence
 in the early 90s, and Pennsylvanian four piece Live have proved to be one
 of the most musically adventurous and stylish bands to remain once the wave
 subsided. Choosing themselves such a confusing name may have betrayed
 a certain nave charm, but 1991's 'Mental Jewelry' was actually, in complete
 contrast, a surprisingly accomplished debut featuring elements of a heavier
 REM and the knowing classic sound of, say, @{"Pearl Jam" link "PEARL JAM"}. However, if 'Mental
 Jewelry' had placed Live at least in the rock audience's consciousness
 then 1994's 'Throwing Copper' would take all the band's sophisticated
 qualities and amplify them a thousand fold. In short, it was an artistic
 and commercial masterpiece, not least because the band had forged a cast
 iron MTV hit in 'I Alone' and its Jonathan Demme-directed video. Curiously
 the album hung around the chart for around a year before actually crawling
 to the number one slot, but part of its success must be attributed to
 a superior talent in songwriting displayed by lead singer and guitarist
 Ed Kowalczyk. Unfortunately, 1997's 'Secret Samadhi' was a rather lumpen
 affair compared to the muscular power of its predecessors but with 1999's
 'The Distance To Here' the band had rediscovered their muse to terrific
 effect and the results were stunningly diverse.

 Recommended listening: 'Throwing Copper'

