@node "LYNYRD SKYNYRD"

 LYNYRD SKYNYRD

 Possibly the finest ever southern rock band to take the stage, the
 influence and musical grandeur of Skynyrd is quite incredible considering
 the tragic history of the band. Since their inception in Jacksonville,
 Florida, in 1965, they have become synonymous with Dixie rock of a very
 distinctive, southern-fried flavour which incorporated both power and
 sweet, sweet melody in almost equal measure. Influenced by the likes of
 Cream, the Rolling Stones, and the Allman Brothers their classic period
 was doubtless the early to mid 70s when they recorded such wondrously
 hard-rocking gems as 'Pronounced Leh-nerd Sky-nerd', 'Second Helping'
 'Nothin' Fancy' and 'Gimme Back My Bullets'.
 Their debut, 'Pronounced...', also gave the band one of the world's most
 enduring rock anthems to the hard-living rock 'n' roll lifestyle in the
 monumental 'Freebird', complete with its epic triple guitar lead break.
 This halcyon period of rollicking honky tonk rock came to a sudden end
 in 1977, however, when the band, having just released the fine 'Street
 Survivors' album, were involved in a plane crash which killed singer
 Ronnie Van Zant, guitarist Steve Gaines, his sister, backing singer
 Cassie Gaines, and personnel manager Dean Kirkpatrick. It took a very
 long time and several line-up and name changes before an outfit displaying
 anything like the power and charm of the original incarnation could evolve.
 But with Ronnie's brother Johnny as the vocalist the band are finally doing
 justice to the memory of their previous incarnation.

 Recommended listening: 'Pronounced Leh-nerd Sky-nerd'

