@node "MACHINE HEAD"

 MACHINE HEAD

 When it comes to modern heavy metal, straight and pure, then California's
 Machine Head are the triumphant leaders in the brutality stakes. Led very
 much from the front by guitarist/vocalist Robb Flynn, the band first
 formed around 1992 with the express desire to be the heaviest, most intense
 metallic experience on the face of the planet. They succeeded. In the wake
 of such pioneering acts as @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"} and @{"Megadeth" link "MEGADETH"}, it was inevitable for
 the new generation to bring something new to the mix and Machine Head did
 so with a touch of hip hop style and a whole lot of angst, which was
 perfect for the grunge period. Expect that Machine Head had nothing to
 with grunge and everything to do with intense emotional pain delivered
 with the punch and precision of a jack hammer to the temple. The band's
 live shows rapidly became the stuff of legend for sheer, brain-shredding
 power while Flynn's tales of inner torment and anguish added an extra
 abrasive edge. This intensity was accurately captured on their 1994 debut
 'Burn My Eyes', and 1997's 'The More Things Change...', both of which
 lodged Machine Head at the vanguard of the nu-metal explosion. 1999's
 'The Burning Red' opened up their sound somewhat, with a greater emphasis
 on melody but with no less weight to their musical muscle.

 Recommended listening: 'Burn My Eyes'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

