@node "MANOWAR"

 MANOWAR

 'Death to False Metal!' was their battle cry - and they definitely meant
 it. When Manowar formed in 1980, their sole aim was to rid the world of
 wimpy false metal and to lead their troops into metal heaven. Or Valhalla.
 Or wherever it is that true metal resides. Led by bassist Joey DeMaio and
 the huge personality of guitarist Ross The Boss, they were such an
 exaggerated outfit that they really didn't require anyone to talk them up.
 They would wear loin clothes, they would play on 11, they even signed their
 record contract in blood! Their magnificently over-the-top image was
 compounded by the music. 1982's glorious debut 'Battle Hymns' was a
 triumphant blow in their epic fight for the music they loved (it even
 featured a guest appearance by Orson Welles on 'Dark Avenger') and 'Into
 Glory Rides', 'Hail To England', 'Fighting The World', 'Sign Of The Hammer'
 and 'Kings Of Metal' were among the albums of the '80s that took the band
 to their peak. They were aggressive, theatrical and totally devoid of a
 sense of irony. The latter album, incredibly, did not feature the sting
 of Ross The Boss, who had left in 1988, but instead featured Death Dealer!
 The band have continued into the '90s and beyond, but have concentrated
 mainly on Europe where their fans - The, er, Army Of The Immortals - are
 most vociferous.

 Recommended listening: 'Battle Hymns'

