@node "MC5"

 MC5

 Along with bands like Iggy And The Stooges, the Motor City 5 - so-called
 because they were formed in Detroit, Michigan - were pioneers in the garage
 style of rock, a genre which led to the punk explosion of the 70s and is
 still cranked out to this day by the likes of Backyard Babies and
 Hellacopters. When the band was first formed back in 1965 by the nucleus
 of Rob Tyner (vocals), Wayne Kramer (guitar) and Fred 'Sonic' Smith
 (guitar) they had limited success with a couple of singles releases,
 but under the guidance of the politically radical DJ and jazz critic
 John Sinclair they became a major musical force by adopting a free-style
 jazz approach to their feedback-drenched thrashes. Espousing revolution
 and political struggle rather than any hippy drippy sentiments of the
 flower power generation they recorded a stunningly powerful live debut
 in the classic 'Kick Out The Jams'. When first released in 1969 the
 record was banned from many retail outlets because of the infamous and
 much-sampled intro rap from Brother J C Crawford which featured the battle
 cry "Kick out the jams, motherfuckers!". Despite the bans the record went
 on to become an iconic release of the time. The band, however, decided to
 go a more commercial route thereafter, soundwise at least, and they parted
 from Sinclair to record 'Back In The USA', another hard-hitting slice of
 primal revolutionary rock. Unfortunately, third album 'High Time' only
 enjoyed a limited success and the band split in 1972.

 Recommended listening: 'Kick Out The Jams'

@endnode


@node "MEGADETH"

 MEGADETH

 Having been unceremoniously booted out of @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"} just as they were
 on the verge of breaking through with their first album, guitarist
 Dave Mustaine became a man driven by the urgent need to be successful
 - just to show his former bandmates that he could do anything they could,
 only better. With the burgeoning thrash scene forming the perfect backdrop,
 Megadeth's career began to parallel that of Metallica's as Mustaine put his
 previous songwriting experience to good use and came up with the chirpily
 titled 'Killing Is My Business And Business Is Good'. The sound was rough,
 but with 1986's 'Peace Sells But Who's Buying', that glitch was ironed out
 and the chunky, speedy, technical style of riffing Megadeth would become
 known for was born. 1988's 'So Far So Good So What?' brought in yet more
 line-up changes as Mustaine kept toying with the make-up of the band.
 The '90s incarnation of the band saw them slowing the pace somewhat and
 with the addition of guitar virtuoso Marty Friedman, the quality of the
 writing became more melodic and considered, though Mustaine was as reliably
 pessimistic as before, dealing with a range of heavy topics such as
 environmental catastrophe and nuclear extinction. With 1999's 'Risk',
 however, Mustaine led the band into almost melodic rock territory.
 The result of this unexpected shift in direction has yet to be determined.

 Recommended listening: 'Peace Sells... But Who's Buying'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'So Far, So Good, So What!'

@endnode


@node "METALLICA"

 METALLICA

 If one had to choose a band that defined the thrash era of the mid-'80s,
 yet had it in them to re-forge their identity for the more media-conscious
 '90s, then these Bay Area reprobates will feature at the top of any
 credible list. Formed ostensibly by drummer Lars Ulrich in 1981, a Danish
 national who had fallen in love with rock music ever since being taken to
 a @{"Deep Purple" link "DEEP PURPLE"} concert by his jazz musician father, Metallica were the
 leading lights of thrash in the '80s and became one of the biggest
 mainstream rock bands of the '90s. Their overtly uncompromising and speedy
 approach to metal led to 'Kill 'Em All', 'Ride The Lightning' and 'Master
 Of Puppets', with the latter 1986 album still considered as one of the most
 inventively intense albums in modern metal. Every single one of these
 records displays the stamp of a band very much steeped in the metallic
 traditions of the New Wave Of British Heavy Metal and influential outfits
 such as @{"Diamond Head" link "DIAMOND HEAD"}. The band's inexorable rise to the top was almost
 derailed by the death of bassist Cliff Burton in a freak road accident
 while on tour in autumn 1986. His replacement was ex-Flotsam and Jetsam
 bassist Jason Newsted and with a revitalised line-up, the band went on to
 release one of the most important albums of the early '90s, their infamous
 eponymous 'black' album. Containing a number of hits singles, including
 'Enter Sandman', this more mid-paced and commercially polished effort
 gave the band license to stretch themselves in all manner of creative
 directions, most recently with their symphonic 'S&M' album.

 Recommended listening: 'Master Of Puppets'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

