@node "MICHAEL SCHENKER"

 MICHAEL SCHENKER

 This supremely talented guitar player actually formed the @{"Scorpions" link "SCORPIONS"} with
 his brother Rudolf in 1971, but spent most of the '70s recording and
 touring with British hard rock legends @{"UFO" link "UFO"}. During this period, the
 eccentric guitarist made a huge name for himself for frenetic and
 impassioned playing - he wasn't so much a technical wizard, as thoroughly
 able to whip up a storming vibe. His UFO highlights are best sampled on
 albums such as 'Force It' and 'Lights Out', but when it was no longer fun
 playing alongside singer Phil Mogg and his alcohol-fuelled bandmates,
 Schenker jumped ship and formed the Michael Schenker Group in 1980.
 One self-titled debut album later, and he had re-invented himself as the
 leader of one of the finest hard rock outfits of the '80s. With 1981's
 confusingly titled follow-up 'MSG', he effectively wrote a theme tune for
 himself with 'Attack Of The Mad Axeman'. At this point, vocalist Gary
 Bardens was replaced by the infinitely more powerful talents of ex-@{"Rainbow" link "RAINBOW"}
 singer Graham Bonnet, and the band's future looked set to be very bright.
 Unfortunately, come the mid to late '80s and the band's line-up seemed to
 involve a revolving door policy as the band became known as the McAuley
 Schenker Group when Far Corporation singer Robin McAuley joined the ranks.
 The quality of the albums became, at best, mundane and Schenker has most
 recently been noodling about with an instrumental album, although a new
 UFO record is currently in the pipeline.

 Recommended listening: 'Michael Schenker Group'


@endnode


@node "MINISTRY"

 MINISTRY

 Delving back into the dim and distant past of some outfits it can be
 remarkable what you'll find, and so it is with Chicago's Ministry. The
 band's current incarnation, and the one they are doubtless best known
 for, casts them as industrial metal pioneers, who along with the likes
 of @{"Nine Inch Nails" link "NINE INCH NAILS"} introduced dance beats and overt use of technology to
 create a bleak and intensely dark sonic assault. When Ministry first came
 into existence, however, in 1981, it was a vehicle for multi-instrumentalist
 Al Jourgensen. The initial Ministry sound was also a lot closer to 80s
 pop bands like Thompson Twins or Depeche Mode. By 1985 this direction had
 changed radically as Jourgensen adopted the harsher sound of Euro-dance
 influences. The late 80s brought many side projects, including Revolting
 Cocks and Lard (with Jello Biafra of Dead Kennedys), which reflected this
 tougher more metalized sound. In the early 90s bassist Paul Barker,
 drummer William Rieflin and occasional vocalist Chris Connelly joined.
 From then on the Ministry machine pumped out dense, aggressive techno-metal
 which has since influenced a whole new generation of industrial style rock
 bands, including, most notably, @{"Marilyn Manson" link "MARILYN MANSON"}. 1988's 'Land Of Rape And
 Honey' started this revolution, followed by 'The Mind Is A Terrible Thing
 To Taste' and the era-defining 'Psalm 69' (1992). Despite the pioneering
 and successful nature of the music Jourgensen still managed to loose
 ground by getting arrested for heroin abuse and it took four years for
 'Filth Pig' to emerge, and another three for the ironically titled
 'Dark Side Of The Spoon' to see the light of day.

 Recommended listening: 'Psalm 69'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "MISFITS"

 MISFITS

 It is probably fair to say that had it not been for some high level
 interest shown in the Misfits by the likes of @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"} and
 @{"Guns N' Roses" link "GUNS N' ROSES"}, then the legendary gorehounds would have languished as
 forgotten underground punk heroes. As it is their raw and succinct hardcore
 bludgeon coupled with a love of b-movie horror flicks has proved to be
 a potent formula, obviously influencing some very notable artists over the
 years - pretty good going, considering the atrocious quality of some of
 the recordings. Originally formed in the mid 70s the most stable personnel
 in the line-up were one Glenn @{"Danzig" link "DANZIG"} (vocals) and Jerry Only (bass).
 A variety of guitarists and drummers came and went, and the band amassed
 a cult following by churning out a series of highly collectible singles
 and EPs. These would eventually be collected into compilations such as
 1985's 'Legacy Of Brutality' and the band only really ever recorded one
 proper album: 'Walk Among Us' (1982). They called it a day in 1983 and
 Danzig went on to form first Samhain then his own eponymous outfit.
 Meanwhile the cult of the Misfits grew throughout the 80s and 90s, thanks
 to various cover versions by the previously mentioned megastars, and then,
 in 1996, Jerry Only decided it was time for the dead to walk again and so
 the chilled corpse of the band was wheeled out of deep freeze and
 re-animated. The results were quite spectacular. With Michael Graves
 (vocals), Doyle Von Frankenstein (guitar) and Dr Chud (drums) on board
 both 'American Psycho' and 'Famous Monsters' stuck closely to the horror
 blueprint only with actual songs and decent production values.

 Recommend listening: 'Famous Monsters'

@endnode


@node "MONSTER MAGNET"

 MONSTER MAGNET

 The epic soundtrack to a twisted and frenzied acid trip, Monster Magnet's
 gargantuan stoned out wall of noise is both deeply spiritual and scary as
 fuck! Not bad going for a bunch of frazzled drug fiends from New Jersey.
 Formed back in 1989 with their space cadet leader guitarist/vocalist Dave
 Wyndorf at the helm, Monster Magnet were one of the first modern bands
 to define the currently trendy 'stoner' sound, along with the likes of
 @{"Kyuss" link "KYUSS"}. More fuzzed up than Blue Cheer, heavier than @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"}, more
 psychedelic than the Summer Of Love, these guys were so reckless and
 deranged they actually tried to dose an audience with acid and were almost
 killed in the ensuing chaos. 1991's 'Spine Of God' was the first full
 length album to mark them out for special attention both critically and
 among the growing 'stoner' cognoscenti. Subsequent LPs 'Superjudge' and
 'Dopes To Infinity' were, if anything, heavier and more acutely honed
 with Wyndorf musing on all manner of unsavoury and cosmic subject matter
 over a welter of concrete slab riffs. The band's most recent adventures
 into mind-expanding hi-fi, however, 'Powertrip', has catapulted them from
 cult status to the general godfathers of the 'stoner' genre. No other band
 of their ilk has lasted quite this long without imploding!

 Recommended listening: 'Powertrip'

@endnode


@node "MORBID ANGEL"

 MORBID ANGEL

 One of the major formative influences on the Florid death metal scene the
 joyously named Trey Azagthoth was inspired to form Morbid Angel in 1984
 in order to bring some real artistry to the more brutal excesses of the
 genre. Still well-respected on the underground scene, the band have
 maintained their cult status, yet brought a great deal of finesse - well,
 as much as is possible! - into their area of expertise. Following the
 occult tenet espoused by Anton LaVey, NDo what thou wilta the band did
 not allow the rules of the genre dictate what or how they could achieve
 anything. When they first started their own sense of quality control kept
 them refining their sound through various gigs and demos for four years
 before they recorded (but never released) 'Abominations Of Desolation'.
 Their first full album was the brutal thrash benchmark 'Altars Of Madness'
 (1989), and since then successive albums - 'Blessed Are The Sick',
 'Covenant', 'Domination' and their most recent studio effort 'Formulas
 Fatal To The Flesh' - have developed the band's sound well beyond the basic
 speed of the genre, introducing elements of sonic experimentation their
 peers could only dream about including.

 Recommended listening: 'Formulas Fatal To The Flesh'

@endnode


@node "MOTLEY CRUE"

 MOTLEY CRUE

 Sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll - a perfectly succinct way to sum up this true
 behemoth of sleazy rock. When Vince Neil (vocals), Mick Mars (guitars),
 Nikki Sixx (bass) and Tommy Lee (drums) came together in LA, in 1981, their
 only grand design was to party. And party they did, often in the most
 controversial and dangerous manner possible - whether it was picking fights
 and fuelling feuds with @{"Guns N' Roses" link "GUNS N' ROSES"}, ODing on heroin or driving a car
 while so drunk that a crash kills you passenger. The latter incident
 involving Vince Neil not only ended the life of @{"Hanoi Rocks" link "HANOI ROCKS"} drummer Razzle
 (and, effectively, the Rocks' youthful career), but it almost finished
 Crue off too. Meanwhile the former incident (involving Sixx, and supposedly
 inspiring the song 'Kickstart My Heart') is only surprising in that no one
 from the band has actually died yet. Still, such a catalogue of bad boy
 behaviour is not that far removed from the music which right from debut
 belter 'Too Fast For Love' was a manifesto for hedonism, a dumb-ass
 nightmare of NY Dolls and @{"Kiss" link "KISS"} trash dressed up in leather and spandex
 and kept erect with far too much hairspray. Crue were immensely derivative
 and yet hugely influential at the same time. Follow-up, 1983's 'Shout At
 The Devil' ensured their status as possibly the world's most dangerous
 band while '85's 'Theatre Of Pain' was a weak blip they'd surely rather
 forget. If those albums at least marked them out for fame then 1987's
 'Girls, Girls, Girls' and 1989's 'Dr Feelgood' are the records for which
 they will be best remembered as down and dirty rockers with a voracious
 appetite for mayhem. Subsequent years have been less than salubrious for
 the band, however, as Neil was ousted for one album before being
 re-instated (in time for 1997's 'Generation Swine'), just in time to see
 Lee bizarrely leaving to pursue a rap career in Methods Of Mayhem.

 Recommended listening: 'Dr. Feelgood'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

