@node "MOTORHEAD"

 MOTORHEAD

 When it comes to full-on pulverizing power, Motorhead have always been,
 and still remain, one of the fastest, nastiest, most unsurpassable of
 metallic experiences. Formed back in 1975 by ex-Hawkwind bassist and
 self-confessed speedfreak Lemmy (aka the tamer-sounding Ian Kilmister),
 the all-time classic line-up consisted of the appropriately monikered
 'Fast' Eddie Clarke (guitar) and Phil 'Philthy Animal' Taylor (drums).
 This titanic trio was responsible for some of the finest rock albums of
 the '70s and '80s. Never less than utterly brutal, they captured the
 speed of punk and harnessed it to the power of more traditional blues
 based metal to produce a uniquely British sound brilliantly captured on
 the likes of 'Overkill', 'Bomber', and the marvellous mayhem of the live
 album 'No Sleep 'Til Hammersmith'. Meanwhile, 'Ace Of Spades' - featuring
 the definitive title track and spoof spaghetti western cover - remains
 a standard to which other rock bands can only aspire. A decidedly dodgy
 patch in the early '80s - due to management problems and line-up changes
 - nevertheless saw Lemmy score again with the likes of 'Orgasmatron' and
 '1916', the latter boasting all manner of experimental touches alongside
 the standard issue brain shredders. With their future as an enduring
 British rock institution assured, the current line-up - including Phil
 Campbell (guitar) and Mikkey Dee (drums) - is all set to release their
 first album of the new millennium.

 Recommended listening: 'No Sleep 'Til Hammersmith'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

