@node "NINE INCH NAILS"

 NINE INCH NAILS

 Although industrial music's roots can be traced way back into the 70s,
 it is without doubt the work of a few noted artists in the 90s that has
 made the genre into such a success. Nine Inch Nails is one such outfit,
 but it is in reality very much a one man band, a vehicle for musician
 Trent Reznor to delve into the dark and tortured recesses of his tormented
 psyche. It was with 1989's 'Pretty Hate Machine' that the Nails phenomenon
 was launched and through repeated MTV play of the single 'Head Like A Hole'
 Reznor soon became the coolest producer of abrasive sounds. A couple of
 very accomplished EPs followed, cunningly titled 'Broken' and 'Fixed'
 respectively and Reznor's status as angstmeister for the MTV generation
 was assured. Reznor was then asked by film-maker Oliver Stone to create
 the soundtrack to the controversial Natural Born Killers in 1994, and
 Reznor's own second album 'The Downward Spiral' was released in the same
 year. Yet again the music was violent and traumatic with the likes of
 singles 'March Of The Pigs' and 'Closer' bringing a somewhat incongruously
 commercial pop edge to proceedings. The fact that the album was recorded
 in the house that Charles Manson's Family murdered actress Sharon Tate
 and her friends added a certain depressing cachet to the already bleak
 catalogue of anguish. A full five years later 'The Fragile' emerged as
 a plush double CD of bile and fury underlining the fact that although
 Reznor is not one of the genres most prolific writers he is, nevertheless,
 one of its most fiercely innovative artists.

 Recommended listening: 'The Downward Spiral'

@endnode


@node "NIRVANA"

 NIRVANA

 If there was one band that epitomised the sound of grunge then it had to be
 Nirvana, the garage rock outfit that emerged from the trailer-park no man's
 land of Aberdeen, Washington, some eight miles outside Seattle, way back
 in 1986. Comprised of Kurt Cobain (guitar/vocals) and Chris Novoselic
 (bass), they went through a succession of drummers before finally settling
 on ex-Scream member Dave Grohl. With something of a landmark album already
 to their name - the fuzz-drenched 'Bleach' emerged in 1989 - the band took
 mainstream rock influences and twisted them beyond all recognition for what
 was to become the most important release of the 1990s. If Cobain had hinted
 at a melodic pop sensibility beneath the grimy production of 'Bleach' then
 'Nevermind' (1991) stripped away the filth and presented his songwriting
 abilities to an unsuspecting public. Unwittingly, Cobain had tapped into
 the zeitgeist of the time. Overtly punk influenced the band turned the
 accepted view of rock upside down and helped create a movement that
 virtually wiped out the bloated big-haired excesses of '80s rock.
 The media coined the phrase Generation X to describe disaffected youth of
 the time and Nirvana provided the soundtrack for an alienated generation,
 a sound and influence still resonant in the music scene today.

 Recommended listening: 'Nevermind'

