@node "NO DOUBT"

 NO DOUBT

 Influenced by the early '80s wave of pop ska peddled by the like of Madness
 and Selecter, Southern California's No Doubt took a relatively long time to
 actually make any major impact on the music scene. Formed way back in 1987
 by vocalist John Spence and brother and sister team Eric (keyboards) and
 Gwen Stefani (vocals), No Doubt's early career was extremely chequered
 - not least because Spence actually committed suicide not long after the
 band formed. With Gwen now the focal point, the band attracted the
 attention of @{"Red Hot Chili Peppers" link "RED HOT CHILI PEPPERS"} bassist Flea who produced a demo for
 them. A few patchy recordings and support slots later, and the band had
 singularly failed to make major headway. When they entered the studio in
 1994 to record 'Tragic Kingdom' (eventually released 1996), things looked
 decidedly shaky and they funded their own sessions. When the album was
 released, however, their timing couldn't have been more perfect.
 With the mid '90s rock scene entertaining such pop-punk acts as @{"Green Day" link "GREEN DAY"},
 No Doubt's punky ska hybrid slotted very nicely into people's expectations.
 And with Gwen's ability to appeal to both girls (as misunderstood female)
 and boys (as a vixen) at once, suddenly the band had effectively turned
 their fortunes around to become one the major rock acts of the '90s.

 Recommended listening: 'Tragic Kingdom'

