@node "OFFSPRING"

 OFFSPRING

 Of all the pogoing hardcore punk outfits to emerge from California, Orange
 County's Offspring must be the most tenacious of the lot. Formed originally
 back in the mid '80s by Dexter Holland (guitarist/vocalist), Noodles
 (guitar) and Greg Kriesel (bass), they eventually added Ron Welty (drums)
 for a thoroughly unremarkable self-titled debut in 1989. They struggled as
 any good punk band should, desperately trying to land a decent recording
 deal. Having signed to Epitaph in the early '90s, their songwriting skills
 having been thoroughly honed in the intervening years, they were ready to
 release 'Ignition' in 1992. The difference between the new Offspring and
 the old was astonishing - but still not astonishing enough to break into
 the wider consciousness. Sure, the playing was tight and powerful; sure,
 Holland's nasal whine was perfect for tales of youthful alienation and
 delivering satirically barbed lyrics; but a little more polish was
 required. In the mid '90s, the climate was just right in the wake of
 grunge for more alternative style bands to bleed into the mainstream
 and with the likes of @{"Green Day" link "GREEN DAY"} already softening up the charts, the
 Offspring's time had come. 'Smash' literally was that - a ripping set of
 hooky punk complete with singles such as 'Come Out And Play' and the UK
 Top 40 hit 'Self Esteem'. Follow-up 'Ixnay On The Hombre' simply gave the
 kids more of what they wanted, but the best was yet to come with 1998's
 'Americana' album and its UK No. 1 hit single, 'Pretty Fly (For A White
 Guy)'. One thing's for sure, they may still have respect in some quarters
 of the hardcore underground, but to everyone else, they're rock stars now!

 Recommended listening: 'Smash'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

