@node "OZZY OSBOURNE"

 OZZY OSBOURNE

 Rock's most likeable loony, Ozzy Osbourne has made a career out of
 acting like a total and utter nutcase. With his early years spent in
 @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"}, Ozzy had already experienced the fraught intensity of
 working in a band, so when he took flight for a solo career in 1978, all he
 wanted to do was make music on his own terms. And, boy, what a fine legacy
 he's left the world of rock. Whether he was creating electrifying rock 'n'
 roll or chewing on doves and live bats, no one could escape the man's
 influence! Although he has continued to record right up to the present day,
 and become the figurehead of one of the most successful touring operations
 of recent years - the enormous Ozzfest experience - his albums have become
 relatively solid and reliable, rather than dazzling. This, however, is in
 stark contrast with his early solo output. With a classic line-up of
 drummer Lee Kerslake (ex-@{"Uriah Heep" link "URIAH HEEP"}), bassist Bob Daisley (ex-@{"Rainbow" link "RAINBOW"}) and
 a certain guitar whiz known as Randy Rhoads (ex-@{"Quiet Riot" link "QUIET RIOT"}), Ozzy created
 some of the finest hard rock albums of the '80s. When 'Blizzard Of Ozz'
 was released in 1980, it was packed with classic tunes, many of which
 still figure in Ozzy's show today; 'Crazy Train', 'Mr Crowley', 'Suicide
 Solution' - the list goes on. With not a single filler in earshot, it was
 a stunning blend of Ozzy's daft sense of humour and the band's incredible
 musical prowess, a feat that was repeated with 1981's marvellous 'Diary Of
 A Madman'. Tragically, Rhoads was killed in a plane crash while on tour in
 the US and although Ozzy deeply mourned the loss of such an immensely
 talented musician, he eventually found another very different, but highly
 skilled individual. Jake E Lee's first Ozzy album was 'Bark At The Moon'
 and he played right through the band's commercial peak during the mid '80s,
 until he was replaced by Zakk Wylde on 1988's 'No Rest For The Wicked'.
 Most recentl,y Ozzy's solo career has been on hold due to the Black Sabbath
 reunion tours, but who knows when rock's original crazy man will strike
 again?

 Recommended listening: 'Blizzard Of Ozz'

