 PANTERA

 These original, self-dubbed 'Cowboys From Hell' are surely one the
 tightest, heaviest metal acts stalking the stages of the world's arenas
 today. But it wasn't always so, because back in the big-haired '80s,
 Pantera were actually closer to a glam band than they might feel
 comfortable admitting to now, with spandex, poodle perms, the works.
 Still, with over five years work - and a brace of albums - already behind
 them, it was with a change of vocalist that they began to mutate into the
 extreme metal titans they surely are today. Singer Phil Anselmo joined
 'Dimebag' Darrel (guitar), Rex Brown (bass) and Vinnie Paul (drums) in
 1986 and 'Power Metal' (1988) was their last flirtation with their
 Kiss-addled past. And if this album already displayed a more marked
 aggression, then that was as nothing compared to the squealing, riffing
 monster unleashed with 'Cowboys From Hell' (1990). The boys, it seemed,
 had only just embraced thrash, but they were to take the genre to hitherto
 unexplored areas. With each successive album, they became increasingly
 angular and brutal; 1992's 'Vulgar Display Of Power' at least contains
 some melody, whereas, say, 1996's 'Great Southern Trendkill' sacrifices
 most of its tunes to the great God Of Riff and Anselmo's barely controlled
 rage. Over more recent years, the band's work rate has dropped off
 somewhat, not least because of Anselmo's near-fatal brush with heroin
 addiction in 1996, but their most recent album, 'Reinventing The Steel',
 at least proves that this particular monster is never going to die easily.

 Recommended listening: 'Vulgar Display Of Power'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

