@node "PARADISE LOST"

 PARADISE LOST

 Few bands can develop so far from their roots and yet retain a sense of
 authentic credibility; Paradise Lost have not only managed to do this with
 great finesse, but with great imagination also. Formed in 1988, in Halifax,
 Yorkshire, the band originally set out as a standard death metal style
 band, all brutal riffs, speed and attitude. But by the time of their 1990
 self-titled debut, they had already ditched the lyrical touchstones of the
 genre for a distinctly arty approach to their existential misery. Chief
 architect in this was vocalist Nick Holmes, whose dour and reflective vocal
 style was infinitely more suited to lyrics of depth and bleakness.
 Keyboards - a definite faux pas for a thrash band! - became more integral
 to their gothic musings and by the time of 1995's 'Draconian Times', they
 were rapidly starting to sound like a very heavy metal Depeche Mode.
 It was 1997's lush and seductive 'One Second' that really clinched the
 transformation, however. Its sleek, dark compositions, featuring electronic
 touches and layers of orchestrated guitars and strings, was a glorious goth
 metal journey through the shaded workings of Holmes' psyche. By the time
 of 'Host', Paradise Lost had established themselves as one of the most
 innovative metal bands of the '90s.

 Recommended listening: 'One Second'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Icon'

