@node "POISON"

 POISON

 Could these super-sleazy kings of bouffant hair be single-handedly
 responsible for depletion of the ozone layer through excessive hairspray
 usage? Possibly, judging by their ridiculously glammed up publicity photos
 of the mid 80s. And to be fair, that was all Bret Michaels (vocals),
 CC DeVille (guitar), Bobby Dall (bass) and Rikki Rockett (drums) ever
 wanted when they formed in 1984 - to be adored. With immaculate timing
 Poison's brainless bubble gum metal hit the spot of a nation still reeling
 from the glitzy successes of bands like @{"Motley Crue" link "MOTLEY CRUE"} and @{"Ratt" link "RATT"}.
 1986's 'Look What The Cat Dragged In' sounded absurdly dumb in places but
 there was no denying the exuberant fun of hits like 'Talk Dirty To Me' and
 its accompanying video. Almost as soon as they had been accepted as
 pop-rockers they decided that longevity lay with being taken seriously and
 1988's 'Open Up And Say...Aah!' contained its fair share of throwaway hits
 and the mega-ballad 'Every Rose Has It's Thorn', a sort of sub @{"Bon Jovi" link "BON JOVI"}
 strum-along bringing to mind lonesome, lovelorn cowboys. With 'Flesh And
 Blood' and 'Native Tongue' in the early 90s the band were straining to
 look credible when all anyone ever wanted them to do was churn out pop
 hits. Since they split and began dabbling in various side projects
 (Michaels has taken an ill-advised side-step into acting) a reunion has
 looked to be on the cards along with a new album.

 Recommended listening: 'Look What The Cat Dragged In'

