@node "PRIMUS"

 PRIMUS

 Primus are a challenge to any lover of great music; there is no doubt that
 the band harbour great talent, but they persist in being wilfully,
 deliberately avant garde when it comes to writing songs. In short, they
 don't. Primus formed back in 1984, but they were always more about
 bassist/vocalist/songwriter Les Claypool's talent than anything else.
 They took the musical prowess of, say, @{"Rush" link "RUSH"} and threw in a whole load
 of Frank Zappa style zaniness to create a bass-popping monster, with
 Claypool's bizarre nasal twang adding that final sonic twist. They didn't
 so much write songs as noodle around with arrangements for a joke.
 At first, they were, naturally, cult heroes, but by early '90s, they had
 developed a reputation to the point where 1993's 'Pork Soda' actually made
 it into the US album charts at No. 10. More recently, their albums 'Tales
 From The Punch Bowl', 'The Brown Album' and 'Antipop' have all turned them
 into bizarre musical stars. Their reputation for overt daffiness even
 landed them the job of creating a theme for hit comedy series 'South Park'.
 Now, that's infamy for you!

 Recommended listening: 'Pork Soda'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Antipop'

