@node "PRODIGY"

 PRODIGY

 The fusion of rap, rock and hip hop may be a relatively standard feature
 of many of today's bands, but not many outfits have successfully adapted
 to more recent popular cultural groundshifts such as rave and techno music.
 The Prodigy, however, have straddled both dance and rock camps with some
 ease over recent years. Starting off in the Essex clubbing heartland back
 in the very early 90s, Liam Howlett was busy demoing material from his
 bedroom. With dancers Leeroy Thornhill and Keith Flint on board and Maxim
 providing some much needed MC talent, they had an underground hit with
 'What Evil Lurks' before 'Charly' - a single based on samples of an old
 public information film - became a top ten hit. At this point the outfit
 were exclusively dance orientated and 'The Prodigy Experience' was a
 massive hit on the rave scene. Howlett - incidentally, the only one of the
 four actually signed as the Prodigy - was already bored by the limited
 scope provided by dance and began to incorporate a more metallic direction
 into 1994's 'Music For The Jilted Generation'. The rockier sensibilities
 fused to the almost punk-like aggression of the beats gave the band a tough
 modern sound quite unlike anything in the charts at the time. By 1996 the
 rock crossover was complete with the release of single 'Firestarter',
 which was stamped with Keith Flint's vocal and visual persona - the video
 showed the dancer in full-on punk freak mode - and ensured the band courted
 plenty of vital publicity. The claustrophobic single 'Breathe' followed and
 the album 'The Fat Of The Land' proved to be a revelation of styles and,
 above all, attitude. Here was music born of the latest anti-authoritarian
 musical movement adapting the styles and focus of punk for the new
 millennium. Howlett, however, ever concerned that the Prodigy should not
 become diluted by over-exposure announced they would cease to exist once
 they had finished touring with the Lollapalooza festival line-up. For the
 time being, at least, the Prodigy appear to be on ice.

 Recommended listening: 'The Fat Of The Land'

