@node "QUEEN"

 QUEEN

 A totally original and unique rock act, Queen not only brought a great
 amount of gut-level energy to their sound through guitarist Brian May's
 distinctive signature sound, but in singer Freddie Mercury they had a
 flamboyant and completely irreplaceable showman. At times whimsical and
 deliberately off the wall Queen were, nevertheless, a superb heavy rock
 band combining considerable power with a very commercial sense of song
 and melody. First coming to prominence in the mid 70s Queen had actually
 formed in 1970 but had assiduously concentrated on building up a live
 reputation. The 'Seven Seas Of Rhye' single proved to be the breakthrough
 in 1974 and the album it came from - the imaginatively titled 'Queen II'
 - led to the band's classic period as with follow-ups 'Sheer Heart Attack'
 and 'A Night At The Opera' they defied expectation by not only being
 stupendously heavy but by throwing in a number of jokes along with
 accomplished classical and operatic flourishes. The latter album is most
 notable for giving the world of music one of it's best-loved tracks in the
 faux operatic 'Bohemian Rhapsody', a single that also kickstarted the
 videos phenomenon through its innovative promo clip. Subsequent LPs
 featured some fine moments and, bar a dubious disco phase with 'Hot Space'
 at the start of the 80s, for much of the big-haired rock decade Queen were
 immensely popular especially after their stunning Live Aid appearance in
 1985. Sadly, by the late 80s rumours about Mercury's poor health were
 beginning to circulate and in 1991 the larger-than-life showman died of
 AIDS. The following year's star-studded tribute concert at Wembley Stadium
 was a testament both to the band's popularity and the esteem in which the
 man was held.

 Recommended listening: 'A Night At The Opera'

@endnode


@node "QUEENSRYCHE"

 QUEENSRYCHE

 The Seattle scene may have been most recently the home of grunge, but in
 the mid '80s, the predominant sound was metal. But not just any kind of
 metal for Geoff Tate (vocals), Chris De Garmo (guitar), Michael Wilton
 (guitar), Eddie Jackson (bass) and Scott Rockenfield (drums) - theirs was
 a titanic, futuristic style of rock, which borrowed heavily from sci-fi
 and fantasy, particularly the '80s 'Mad Max' phenomenon. Hence, after
 releasing their eponymous debut EP and a solid but unexciting debut
 called 'The Warning', Queensryche suddenly found themselves persuaded to
 done the most preposterously over-the-top outfits in an attempt to add
 a suitably visual dimension to their hysterically overblown sound.
 Fortunately, the big hair, make-up and wide-load shoulder pads didn't last
 long, but the music was another matter entirely. With 'Rage For Order',
 they experimented with a gleamingly polished production and with 1988's
 'Operation: Mindcrime', they did the unthinkable: they created a masterly
 metallic concept album that wasn't just good - it was terrific. In fact,
 it was more than that, it was a classic with its story line of revolution,
 futuristic dystopias and evil megalomaniac professors. Follow up 'Empire'
 aspired to equally great heights, as did subsequent less successful albums.
 Most recently, the band have been re-grouping and re-defining themselves
 following the departure of key songwriter De Garmo shortly before the
 recording of their latest album 'Q2K'.

 Recommended listening: 'Operation: Mindcrime'

@endnode


@node "QUICKSAND"

 QUICKSAND

 To most people hardcore is simply about lots of shouting over a barely
 competent musical background, but to New York's Quicksand it was always
 a springboard into deeply heartfelt lyrical sentiments - about love, loss,
 childhood, politics - firmly harnessed to a more progress sense of melody
 and song structure. When the band first formed in the late 80s the line-up
 consisted of true hardcore veterans: vocalist/guitarist Walter Schreifels
 had been a member of Youth Of Today and the legendary Gorilla Biscuits,
 guitarist Tom Capone had been a member of Bold, bassist Sergio Vega had
 been a member of Absolution, and drummer Alan Cage had been a member of
 Beyond. With these punk and hardcore credentials it was natural for the
 band to churn out the hardest, heaviest music they could, but Quicksand
 rapidly became noted not just for their power but their subtlety. Theirs
 was a more groove-based sound, often likened to Helmet for its heaviness.
 Their constant touring in the early 90s with the likes of Helmet, Rage
 Against The Machine, and Fugazi ironically led to them signing to major
 label Polydor and a fine debut album in 'Slip'. The textures of the debut
 were expanded upon with 1995 follow-up 'Manic Compression', an all together
 more complex record which stretched hardcore's generic sound to the limit.
 Though the band seemed to run out of steam and split for a while to pursue
 other musical goals, they reconvened in 1998 and toured with the @{"Deftones" link "DEFTONES"},
 promising that an album would follow.

 Recommended listening: 'Manic Compression'

@endnode


@node "QUIET RIOT"

 QUIET RIOT

 Some bands are destined to be of interest because of who used to play in
 their ranks rather than for any major musical merit of their own, and so
 it is with these LA rockers, who originally formed in the '70s but enjoyed
 their success in the '80s. The band had always had commercial leanings to
 their glitzy hard rock sound and in the '70s they were fortunate enough to
 enjoy the talents of a remarkably talented guitarist: Randy Rhoads. The two
 albums Rhoads featured on are highly prized now by collectors and by all
 accounts, this legendary guitarist's talents are very much in evidence.
 Rhoads, however, famously jumped ship to join @{"Ozzy Osbourne" link "OZZY OSBOURNE"}'s band in
 1979, and Quiet Riot were left to remould themselves, which they duly did,
 and proceeded to enjoy the most successful period of their careers.
 They brought in a touch more melody, threw in a belting chorus or two and
 came back with 1983's 'Metal Health', which hit the No. 1 spot and sold
 over 5 million copies on the back of some sparky singles action, not least
 their crackling cover of the old Slade classic 'Cum On Feel The Noize'.
 It was a remarkable feat of re-engineering, but the momentum didn't last,
 and, though subsequent albums sold respectably, they never attained the
 same degree of success. The band split in 1988, but vocalist Kevin DuBrow
 has attempted too resuscitate Quiet Riot a couple of times since.

 Recommended listening: 'Metal Health'

