@node "RAGE AGAINST THE MACHINE"

 RAGE AGAINST THE MACHINE

 Some bands have to slog around for years before they make their mark either
 in commercial or artistic terms, but LA's Rage Against The Machine struck
 gold in both senses virtually from their inception. Formed in 1992 by
 Zack de la Rocha (vocals), Tom Morello (guitar), Timmy C (bass) and
 Brad Wilk (drums), they took the fashionable tenets of hip-hop and rap,
 threw in some wild funk and blasted it all out in proud heavy metal
 fashion. It was a sound and style which hit its mark with unnerving
 accuracy. Their self-titled 1993 album was a howling tirade of abuse
 and fury aimed at authority in whatever guise that may appear and struck
 a chord with the disaffected and alienated the world over. Chief among the
 rabble-rousing anthems was the expletive-strewn 'Killing In The Name',
 which soon had moral guardians calling for them to be banned. Adding more
 fuel to the fire of controversy were singles 'Bullet In The Head' and
 'Bombtrack'. Following this period, the band spent time aligning themselves
 with various worthy causes, proving that when it came to protest, they were
 a lot more than just mouth pieces for empty political rhetoric. Still, all
 this activity outside the studio mean that it was 1996 before 'Evil Empire'
 emerged, and another three before 'The Battle Of Los Angeles'.
 Nevertheless, both albums proved that when it came to self-belief and
 a righteous sense of anger, RATM had lost none of their potency.

 Recommended listening: 'Rage Against The Machine'

