@node "RAINBOW"

 RAINBOW

 One of the definitive hard rock bands of the '70s, Rainbow was actually
 formed by ex-@{"Deep Purple" link "DEEP PURPLE"} guitarist Ritchie Blackmore from the remains of
 US band Elf. Having left his Purple bandmates, Blackmore wanted a vehicle
 for himself that he could control himself. Elf had supported Purple on
 a previous tour and their frontman, @{"Ronnie James Dio" link "DIO"}, was a man with
 a voice tailor-made for metallic opera. All Blackmore did, in effect,
 was to hire all of Elf... except their guitarist! Under the catchy name
 Ritchie Blackmore's Rainbow, they released a self-titled debut in 1975
 and with the guitarist's classic leanings and Dio's love of fantasy lyrics,
 a classic was born. Trimming the name to a more pronounceable Blackmore's
 Rainbow, the world got 'Rainbow Rising' in 1976, one of rock's finest
 albums featuring stage faves like 'Tarot Woman' and the epic 'Stargazer'.
 1978's 'Long Live Rock 'N' Roll' proved to be the last album Dio would
 appear on. In fact, several other band members also found themselves on
 the wrong end of Blackmore's notorious perfectionism - or should that be
 irascible moodiness? Whatever, with new singer Graham Bonnet, the revamped
 line-up enjoyed their greatest commercial period as 'Down To Earth' brought
 Top 10 hits with 'Since You've Been Gone' and 'All Night Long'. And then
 Blackmore decided things still weren't right and Joe Lynn Turner found
 himself as vocalist for 1981's 'Difficult To Cure', which contained hit
 single 'I Surrender'. However, by this point, Blackmore was trying to make
 the band a slicker, tighter, melodic hard rock band, rather than the
 neo-classic outfit it had originally been. 'Straight Between The Eyes'
 and 'Bent Out Of Shape' were fine in themselves, but couldn't match the
 bombastic majesty of the '70s albums, and the band fizzled out in 1983.

 Recommended listening: 'Rainbow Rising'

@endnode


@node "RAMMSTEIN"

 RAMMSTEIN

 In German Rammstein literally means a battering ram. A ram made of rock.
 Very appropriate when you consider what this intense sextet from East
 Germany actually sound like. Formed in 1993 the band quickly developed
 a unique voice similar in some ways to the marching metallic thunder of,
 say, KMFDM, which principally piled layers of regimented guitar over
 a rigidly pumping rhythm section finished off with the baritone operatic
 growl of singer Till Lindemann. The fact that Lindemann was once an Olympic
 class swimmer might explain where he gets such awesome lung power.
 In addition to the intimidating potency of the music Rammstein also
 incorporated elements of perverse theatrics into their set. It wouldn't be
 unusual for Lindemann to sing his bizarre tales of lost love while totally
 on fire. This provocative combination of freak art and rock 'n' roll was at
 the focus of debut LP 1995's 'Herzeleid' (Heartache), a record strange
 enough to attract the attention of film maker David Lynch who was suitably
 impressed enough to include two tracks in his Lost Highway film.
 The industrially stark discipline of the Rammstein sound was even more
 pronounced on follow-up 'Sehnsucht' (Longing) which entered the German
 chart at number one and almost repeated the feat in Switzerland and
 Austria. Strangely, doubtless helped by MTV, the Rammstein phenomenon
 also appears to be gathering pace in America where the band's overt blend
 of violence and romanticism has both baffled and outraged in equal measure.

 Recommended listening: 'Sehnsucht'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Live Aus Berlin'

