@node "RAMONES"

 RAMONES

 Could the brothers Ramone be the most famous and influential punk band
 ever? Possibly. Originally formed in 1974, Johnny, Joey, Dee Dee and Tommy
 dubbed themselves after the poorest families in Noo Yoik city and created
 a punk sound - complete with touches of '60s pop (which they loved) - that
 would heavily influence the world of rock pretty much for ever.
 They specialised in short, sharp, shocking blasts of buzz saw guitars,
 lyrics that dealt with some of the dumbest subjects you could possibly
 think of, and a scruffy, fuck-you nihilism that influenced everyone from
 the @{"Sex Pistols" link "SEX PISTOLS"} (they were apparently Sid Vicious' favourite band) to
 @{"Nirvana" link "NIRVANA"}. When the Ramones' 1976 self-titled debut emerged, the world got
 such classics as 'Now I Wanna Sniff Some Glue' and 'Blitzkrieg Bop' with
 its chantalong 'Hey ho let's go!' refrain. Every single album that followed
 stuck rigidly to this philosophy: make 'em dumb, make 'em catchy, make 'em
 fast. In fact, on stage the songs were played even faster. The years ticked
 by and the Ramones continued to turn out the classics, although their '70s
 period is always remembered with greatest affection, until it just stopped
 being fun any more and they called it a day in the mid '90s.

 Recommended listening: 'Rocket To Russia'

@endnode


@node "RATT"

 RATT

 Sleaze, glamour, spandex, hair - welcome to the superficial world of LA's
 Ratt, one of the tackiest, trashiest rock bands to emerge from the club
 scene of the early '80s. Originally formed in the late '70s as Mickey Ratt,
 the line-up of singer Stephen Pearcy, guitarists Robbin Crosby and Warren
 DeMartini, bassist Juan Croucier and drummer Bobby Blotzer would go on to
 major success in the glitzy '80s. Typically, a self-financed eponymous
 debut led to a major deal and 1984's 'Out Of The Cellar', a huge hard
 rock success with single 'Round And Round' securing the band airplay on
 radio-playlists across America. They were at their best during this period,
 with basically every single song concentrating on the business of sex and
 fun. Follow-up 'Invasion Of Your Privacy' (1985) delivered more of the same
 and turned the band into arena-filling superstars. Into the late '80s,
 the Ratt formula continued virtually unchanged with a relatively constant
 level of success, even though the critics began to pan everything the band
 did. On the one hand, Ratt were shallow and limited, but on the other,
 they satisfied a craving for instantly catchy pop rock tunes.
 Stephen Pearcy eventually left in 1992 to create his own band, but there
 was a modest self-titled reunion album in 1999.

 Recommended listening: 'Out Of The Cellar'

@endnode


@node "RED HOT CHILI PEPPERS"

 RED HOT CHILI PEPPERS

 Funk and punk - an unlikely combination of genres, but one which this
 bunch of Hollywood reprobates would make their own, virtually creating
 a genre in itself and spawning thousands of imitators who wanted to
 groove with the same degree of aplomb. Originally conceived back in 1983,
 their first self-titled album was a curious hotch-potch of sleazy funk
 and shin-chewing punk which suffered from the fact that, for reasons far
 too complicated to explain here, only two of the real band members were
 present for the recordings - singer Anthony Keidis and bass monster Flea!
 1985's 'Freaky Styley' was far more successful with production duties
 being handled by the arch-funkmeister himself George Clinton. But these
 relatively smooth and funky sounds were revved up to a sexually charged
 maximum with subsequent albums, most notably 'Mother's Milk' and their
 all-time classic 'Blood sugar sex magik' (1991). With the latter, they
 achieved their intention of creating a full-blooded, pumping, funk punk
 hybrid, featuring both their sensitive side ('Under the Bridge') and their
 debauched side ('Suck My Kiss'). It was a triumph which would overshadow
 their subsequent albums, even though the quality was always high.
 Most recently, 1999's 'Californication' has seen the band reach new highs,
 so to speak, with their strongest set of songs yet.

 Recommended listening: 'Blood sugar sex magik'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

