@node "RUSH"

 RUSH

 Canada can't exactly claim to be home to many classic rock bands, but
 Toronto-based Rush are one of the best, not just in the land of the
 Maple leaf, but the entire world. Initially formed back in 1968, they
 were originally heavily influenced by the likes of @{"Led Zeppelin" link "LED ZEPPELIN"} and Cream,
 and this showed through markedly on their 1975 self-titled debut.
 The classic line-up of bassist/vocalist Geddy Lee, guitarist Alex Lifeson
 and drummer Neil Peart proved that there was a lot more to them than that,
 however. They would evolve, in effect, into a genre themselves; no one else
 could do what this trio could do, and over the years, they have developed
 a style best described, rather loosely, as a kind of art rock. Their
 initial forays into lyric writing involved basic fantasy themes, but with
 Peart's love of literature and all things scientific and intellectual, the
 songs eventually began to reflect his interests. Musically, also, they were
 unparalleled for their dedication and professionalism, a fact which was
 borne out consistently by their epic concept pieces, most notably the
 brilliant '2112' album. In fact, it was this peak period of the '70s and
 '80s that best marked out the band's talents. 1977's 'A Farewell To Kings',
 1978's epic 'Hemispheres', 1981's punchy, hard rocking 'Moving Pictures'
 - all these, and the albums in between, show a band capable of both
 stunning musical performances and almost endless amounts of invention.
 Rush have now, understandably, reached the point where they can ease off
 in terms of work rate, and do pretty much whatever they want musically.
 But whenever a Rush album is expected, the event is always momentous and
 fascinating.

 Recommended listening: '2112'

