@node "SAMMY HAGAR"

 SAMMY HAGAR

 These days, curly-haired all-American boy Sammy Hagar is best known for
 doing the nigh on impossible and stepping into the enormous empty shoes
 left by @{"David Lee Roth" link "DAVID LEE ROTH"} when he agreed to front @{"Van Halen" link "VAN HALEN"} back in 1985.
 This remarkably successful period of rock history aside, Hagar's career
 actually stretches back to the early '70s and a couple of stonking albums
 he recorded with Montrose where in he was the vocalist, and writer of some
 of the best songs the band had in their set. 'Montrose' (1973) and 'Paper
 Money' (1974) contained such Hagar-attributed classics as 'Bad Motor
 Scooter', 'Rock The Nation' and 'Space Station No. 5'. With his ability
 to pen superbly powerful rock songs proven, he went solo in 1975 and made
 eight studio albums, beginning with the cheekily titled 'Nine On A Ten
 Scale'. Commercial success was elusive at first, but then finally arrived
 with '79's 'Street Machine', which, true to type, featured yet more songs
 about cars, girls, cars, love, and, erm, did we forget to mention the cars?
 He even wrote a song about his beloved Trans Am! During the period right up
 to his joining Van Halen, he was well-known but it was this amazing career
 move that actually made his name on a global scale.

 Recommended listening: 'Street Machine'

@endnode


@node "SAXON"

 SAXON

 Some bands just will not die, and the honest-to-goodness metal ethic
 espoused by this tough outfit from Barnsley, Yorkshire, is a testament
 to their undying love of rock music. Originally formed as Son Of A Bitch,
 Saxon came to prominence during the late '70s and early '80s as one of
 the chief bands at the vanguard of the New Wave Of British Heavy Metal.
 There was nothing fancy about their down 'n' dirty brand of rock, it was
 all about girls, rock 'n' roll and excitement - the lyrics were often
 ridiculous, but you couldn't faults the ballsy riffing provided by
 guitarists Paul Quinn and Graham Oliver. Their no-nonsense style was
 stamped all the way through such wondrous albums as 'Wheels Of Steel',
 'Strong Arm Of The Law' and 'Denim And Leather'. It was a simple template,
 but one that would influence literally thousands of copyists.
 Arguably at their peak in the early '80s, their attempts at cracking
 America led them to experiment with a smoother sound, and with the
 invention of thrash metal, they found themselves somewhat alienated.
 This led to a general decline in their fortunes, although they have
 continued to churn out the albums - with a notably tougher sound than
 some of the late '80s fare - and continue touring to this day.

 Recommended listening: 'Wheels Of Steel'

@endnode


@node "SCORPIONS"

 SCORPIONS

 For all their love of metal, it's a little odd to think that Germany has
 only produced one lasting world-ranking rock band: the mighty Scorpions.
 Originally formed in 1971, this Teutonic outfit began by dabbling in all
 things psychedelic to varying degrees of success, but they gradually
 shifted away from those roots to become one of Germany's premier metal
 acts. Beginning with 1976's 'Virgin Killers' (and its extremely dubious
 sleeve art - a feature they would become noted for), they headed down the
 road of revved up axes and chunky hard rock. The very peak of this period
 is best displayed by the headbanging fury of 1979's 'Lovedrive' and 1980's
 'Animal Magnetism', both of them housed in suitably strange sleeve art yet
 again. What made this lot so successful was their unerring ear for a hooky
 tune, but, most importantly, the ability to ram the point home with no
 uncertain degree of enthusiasm. Their infectious energy was always apparent
 in concert, and live albums like 'Tokyo Tapes' and 'World Wide Live' are
 a testament to this fact. What truly broke the band on a global scale,
 however, was the, frankly surprising, 'Wind Of Change' hit single, complete
 with whistling solo! To this day, the band continue to tour and record,
 though with less success after the advent of grunge.

 Recommended listening: 'Lovedrive'

@endnode


@node "SCREAMING TREES"

 SCREAMING TREES

 Always lumped in with the Seattle grunge crew, in reality, this very fine
 rock band were formed and based in Ellensburg, Washington. They were also
 very little to do with grunge - they just happened to be in the area when
 it all happened. They had actually formed back in 1985 and brought together
 a variety of influences ranging from '60s psychedelia and punk through to
 heavy metal and, dare we suggest, a hint of blues and country. The latter
 aspects can be seen shining through on singer Mark Lanegan's superlative
 solo work, but when they first began, his morose lyrical phrasing and the
 band's wall of riffs fitted in quite nicely with the alienation of grunge.
 Three solid albums passed before their Chris Cornell (@{"Soundgarden" link "SOUNDGARDEN"})
 produced 'Uncle Anaeasthesia' (1991), and it all suddenly made sense.
 The songs were lush, powerful, passionate and appeared to plumb the very
 pits of despair - this was beauty found in mental and spiritual anguish.
 With time taken out to pursue solo projects, 1996's gorgeous 'Dust' was,
 eventually, the perfect amalgamation of all their disparate elements;
 there were splashes of '60s and '70s style rock, touches of country,
 tales of sin and redemption. Since then, the band have effectively been
 in suspended animation with Lanegan seemingly the most industrious as he
 continues to record diverse and soulful rock records in grand style.

 Recommended listening: 'Dust'

@endnode


@node "SEPULTURA"

 SEPULTURA

 Possibly the only world class thrash band to emerge from Brazil, Sepultura
 were one hell of a noisy crew when they formed in 1984, in Belo Horizonte.
 Their initial line-up featured brothers Igor (drums) and Max Cavalera
 (guitar/vocals), along with Jairo T and Paulo Jnr (bass), and they were
 immensely influenced by the likes of @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"}, @{"Venom" link "VENOM"} and @{"Slayer" link "SLAYER"}.
 In fact, they borrowed wholesale from the latter and rapidly made a name
 for themselves as the fastest, most brutally aggressive thrash band on the
 continent, with songs steeped in cod satanic imagery at this time and
 themes of horror and insanity running throughout.
 Debut album 'Morbid Visions' (1986) was solid, but uninspiring, and
 'Schizophrenia' did little to dispel the idea that they were copyists.
 With new guitarist Andreas Kisser replacing Jairo T, however, the band
 gradually began to develop into a seriously talented outfit. 1989's
 'Beneath The Remains' took on more of a political flavour as Max began
 exercising his lyrical brains beyond demons and devils.
 With 'Arise' (1991) and 'Chaos AD' (1993), the band effectively paved the
 way for what would be their finest, most diverse work. Already hints of
 tribal rhythms and experimentation were prevalent, but in 1996, they
 shocked the world of metal with the raw splendour of 'Roots'. It featured
 plenty of guitar and vocal violence, but the inclusion of traditional
 Brazilian percussive elements and instrumentation made it truly unique.
 In addition, the aggressive and bass-heavy grind they had been developing
 was finally perfected, a style which has been adopted wholesale by many
 so-called nu-metal bands. Although Max has now split off from the rest of
 the band to form his own outfit @{"Soulfly" link "SOULFLY"}, Sepultura continue to record and
 tour with new singer Derrick Green.

 Recommended listening: 'Roots'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Arise'

@endnode


@node "SEX PISTOLS"

 SEX PISTOLS

 Were they created by manager Malcolm McLaren or would they have happened
 anyway? This type of question has been brought up time after time when
 trying to analyse the shocking punk phenomenon that was the Sex Pistols.
 Ultimately, though, who cares? The fact remains that, for a short period
 of time, Johnny Rotten (vocals), Steve Jones (guitar), Paul Cook (drums)
 and first Glen Matlock, then Sid Vicious (bass), were the most important
 rock band in the world. Their influence can be seen in everyone from
 @{"Guns N' Roses" link "GUNS N' ROSES"} to @{"Nirvana" link "NIRVANA"}. They only recorded one album, the all-time punk
 classic 'Never Mind The Bollocks Here's The Sex Pistols', but with this
 single record to their name, they changed the face of modern music forever.
 It was a raucous, toxic, gleefully rebellious record simply brimming over
 with bile and poison. It gave them a number of UK hit singles and succeeded
 in getting them banned just about everywhere they tried to play. Perhaps
 the most salient point to make about a band with such a small body of work,
 but with such a huge influence, is that they were, effectively, the focal
 point of a nation in crisis. The wasteland of mid-'70s Britain was a bleak
 place to be if you were a teenager and the music scene seemed to be
 populated with bloated rock star gods who were very far removed from
 the fans that elevated them to that status. The Pistols cut through this
 bullshit, questioned authority and made enemies out of just about anyone
 they crossed paths with - including several record companies, who actually
 paid the band to get them off their labels. Inevitably, with such
 a volatile bunch of musicians, and Sid Vicious' spiralling heroin
 addiction, the band were destined to self-destruct in spectacular
 fashion. And they did so while on tour in the US in 1978.

 Recommended listening: 'Never Mind The Bollocks'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

@endnode


@node "SILVERCHAIR"

 SILVERCHAIR

 Imitation is the sincerest form of flattery and anyone listening to
 Australia's silverchair wouldn't be far off the mark in assuming that
 school friends Daniel Johns (guitar/vocals), Chris Joannu (bass), and
 Ben Gillies (drums) had more than a passing acquaintance with the Seattle
 grunge scene. The actual story behind the band is the stuff of fairy tales;
 three friends win a national radio station competition and the prize is
 a recording session. This led to a hit single, and fame beckoned with their
 first album 1995's 'Frogstomp'; the band were still at school and they were
 rock stars already, with their parents as managers. The remarkable thing
 about 'Frogstomp' was its very professional and imitative qualities.
 While it was true that the band owed a great deal to their parents' old
 record collections (they used to practise old @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"} and @{"Deep Purple" link "DEEP PURPLE"}
 songs when rehearsing), the angsty, downtuned metallic grind was immensely
 reminiscent of the Seattle sound. The clinching factor was Johns'
 remarkable, though allegedly unintentional, Eddie Vedder (@{"Pearl Jam" link "PEARL JAM"}) -
 style vocals. Needless to say, their re-creation of this already familiar
 sound made a huge impact on the US, and 1997's 'Freak Show' did nothing to
 dispel the comparisons with @{"Nirvana" link "NIRVANA"}. Even their choice of song titles -
 'Abuse Me', 'Slave', 'Freak' - seemed to ape the grungers. The band's most
 recent record - 1999's 'Neon Ballroom' - has been something of a surprise,
 with a hitherto unexpected degree of maturity and musical variety marking
 out a definite path for the future.

 Recommended listening: 'Frogstomp'

@endnode


@node "SKID ROW"

 SKID ROW

 The story of New Jersey band Skid Row's entry into the world of rock is
 something of a legend now. Originally guitarist Dave 'Snake' Sabo and
 @{"Jon Bon Jovi" link "BON JOVI"} grew up together and they vowed that should one of them hit
 the big time in show biz he would come back and give the other a little
 help. Bon Jovi, of course, became mega stars and so Jon duly helped his
 mate's fledgling outfit get started. Had he not helped, however, it's
 highly likely that Skid Row would have got there in the end. Not only did
 they have some fantastically melodic and super-tough rock songs, they also
 possessed hyperactive wunderkind Sebastian Bach on vocals. Songs like
 'Youth Gone Wild' could have been penned with Sebastian in mind and it was
 with tunes like this that their eponymous 1989 debut was packed. Theirs was
 the sound of disaffected youth channeled into music but they also knew the
 value of a good pop tune when they released the likes of ballad 'I Remember
 You'. Their uncompromising nature led to a super-heavy follow-up, 1991's
 'Slave To The Grind', which surprisingly eschewed the commercial path laid
 down by their debut and opted instead for balls-out fury. The punk
 influence evident before finally made itself known in no uncertain terms
 when the @{"Sex Pistols" link "SEX PISTOLS"}' 'Holidays In The Sun' backed a single release of
 'Wasted Time'. Sadly, however, with such a promising start third album
 'Subhuman Race' took a long time arriving (it emerged in 1995) and interest
 in the band fizzled out.

 Recommended listening: 'Skid Row'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

