@node "SLAYER"

 SLAYER

 For some the pinnacle of thrash always was, and always will be, represented
 by the infernal tornado of noise that is Slayer in full, dark flight.
 Formed in Los Angeles in 1981 the classic line-up consisted of Tom Araya
 (bass/vocals), Kerry King (guitar), Jeff Hanneman (guitar) and drummer
 Dave Lombardo. They came together with only one intention in mind: to be
 the fastest, sickest, heaviest metal band on the face of the planet.
 And some would argue they still are. At first their sub-@{"Venom" link "VENOM"} black metal
 stylings were rather lamentable but as their perfectionism grew their
 ability to stun and outrage grew also. Their 'Haunting The Chapel' EP
 (1984) went some way to making their reputation with its blistering thrash
 attack. But their mean-spirited bluster found its full expression on 1985's
 'Hell Awaits', an intense overtly Satanic slab of metal. It got them a deal
 with legendary Def Jam records and producer Rick Rubin was at the helm of
 their finest record to date, an album which has influenced countless
 pretenders to the throne of thrash ever since: 'Reign In Blood'.
 It was less than forty minutes in length but each one of those minutes was
 packed with more poison and spite than most bands can muster over an entire
 career. Fans loved it, the moral guardians hated it. A legend was born.
 Subsequent releases have found the band experimenting more with pace and
 dynamics but still at the core of albums such as 'South Of Heaven' and
 'Seasons In The Abyss' lies a perennial fascination with brutal, naked
 speed and the satanic occult.

 Recommended listening: 'Reign In Blood'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Seasons In The Abyss'

