@node "SOUNDGARDEN"

 SOUNDGARDEN

 Never really a grunge band as such, Soundgarden did, nevertheless, form
 in Seattle but their more overtly metallic brand of alternative rock found
 them sitting ill at ease among the new generation of slacker rock. After
 all they had actually been around since 1984 and had very little to do
 with the misery of Generation X, even though their style of music was
 loaded with melancholic power. No, for singer Chris Cornell and crew -
 most notably ace guitarist Kim Thayil - the sound of @{"Black Sabbath" link "BLACK SABBATH"} was
 more of an inspiration and their love of psychedelia is also apparent on
 their 1988 debut 'Ultra Mega OK'. Thayil was a fine craftsman when it came
 to poetic riffs and the superlative musicianship clearly counterpointed
 Cornell's love of the bleak and desperate. 'Louder Than Love' was
 a superbly wrought follow up but with the angsty fire of 'Bad Motorfinger',
 Soundgarden's love of 70s style rock was given a thoroughly modern sheen
 and chart action resulted. This, however, was as nothing compared to the
 dark joys present on 'Superunknown' the album that contained such
 wondrously bleak songs as 'Fell On Black Days' and 'Black Hole Sun'.
 This was thinking man's rock, all introverted moods and subsumed passion.
 By the time of 1996's 'Down On The Upside' they had opened up a little
 - but not a lot - and the claustrophobic genius of early records was still
 in evidence. However, by this point internal friction eventually led to
 the band suddenly splitting in early 1997.

 Recommended listening: 'Superunknown'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

