@node "STATUS QUO"

 STATUS QUO

 These perennial twelve-bar boogie merchants will, seemingly, go on forever.
 The roots of the band stretch all the way back to 1962 but it was the
 classic line-up of Francis Rossi (guitar/vocals), Alan Lancaster (bass),
 Rick Parfitt (guitar/vocals), and John Coghlan (drums) that recorded their
 first hit the psychedelic 'Pictures Of Matchstick Men' in 1967. It wasn't
 until 1970, however, that they actually began to adopt their hugely
 successful twelve-bar formula with the 'Dog Of Two Head' album. With this
 basic blueprint in mind the Quo boys merely piled on the energy and let
 loose a brace of commercially successful albums which appealed to just
 about everyone and their mothers - 'Piledriver', 'Hello', 'Quo', 'On The
 Level', they all spawned huge chart hits. And the band simply kept rocking
 all the way through punk, with a cover of John Fogerty's 'Rockin' All Over
 The World' topping the chart during 1977! Come the early 80s and a brief
 split led to Rossi and Parfitt being the only original members left, but
 still they trundled on with the hits flowing. While the 70s flavour of the
 band had definitely been hard rock, the 80s gradually turned into something
 all together more dreary signalled by the hideous 'In The Army Now' in
 1986. The band have continued well into the 90s though anyone easily upset
 by good rock gone most definitely bad should avoid their increasingly lame
 offerings and head straight for the golden 70s.

 Recommended listening: 'Quo'

