@node "STEVE VAI"

 STEVE VAI

 Finger-flinging axemen don't come more flamboyant or talented than this
 charismatic performer. And let's face it when it comes to teachers Steve
 Vai has had some of the best. Vai first started taking guitar lessons from
 the great @{"Joe Satriani" link "JOE SATRIANI"} back in the early 70s while playing in a variety of
 teenage rock outfits but his real break came when he joined Frank Zappa's
 band in the very early 80s. During this period he managed one solo effort
 in the shape of 'Flex-able', a diverse and original showcase of his guitar
 virtuosity. A brief spell in hard-rock legends Alcatrazz led first to
 ex-@{"Sex Pistol" link "SEX PISTOLS"} Johnny Lydon's Public Image Ltd then to a two album stint
 with @{"David Lee Roth" link "DAVID LEE ROTH"}. Finally the end of the 80s brought a dazzling display
 of guitar mayhem for @{"Whitesnake" link "WHITESNAKE"}'s 'Slip Of The Tongue'. Vai's playing was
 superb but ill-suited to such cock-rock shenanigans. While recording the
 latter he had begun work on his own solo project and when it emerged in
 1990 'Passion And Warfare' was a stunningly assured mix of technical
 precision and off-the-wall conceptual humour - clearly his time with
 Zappa had influenced him a great deal. With each successive album -
 'Sex & Religion', 'Alien Love Secrets', 'Fire Garden', 'The Ultra Zone'
 - Vai has attempted to bring different styles and flavours to his work
 rather than to simply peddle blisteringly complex runs of notes. The same
 desire to entertain is also prevalent in his stage show which incorporates
 all manner of theatrical showmanship to complement the pyrotechnic
 instrumental display.

 Recommended listening: 'Passion And Warfare'

