@node "STONE TEMPLE PILOTS"

 STONE TEMPLE PILOTS

 As an example of what can happen when rock stars get their hands on too
 much money and too many drugs, Stone Temple Pilots fit the bill all too
 well. As ever the band's roots lie back in the mists of time when singer
 Scott Weiland and bassist Robert Deleo were dating the same girl.
 They naturally met and a partnership was struck which eventually became
 Stone Temple Pilots in 1991 with the addition of Robert's guitarist brother
 Dean and drummer Eric Ketz. At a time when grunge was at the height of
 fashion the Pilot's riff heavy melodies and driving punk attitude fitted
 directly into what people wanted and the band rapidly found themselves
 in the same company as @{"Alice In Chains" link "ALICE IN CHAINS"} and @{"Pearl Jam" link "PEARL JAM"}. 1992's 'Core'
 virtually made stars of them overnight with its tales of thwarted romance
 and youthful alienation. Follow-ups 'Purple' and 'Tiny Music Songs From The
 Vatican Gift Shop' provided more stunning MTV-friendly rock with splashes
 of psychedelia colouring the brazenly driving riffage. The band were hugely
 successful with their seemingly effortless mix of melody and heaviosity.
 But even as they appeared to be unconquerable heroes Weiland's drug
 dependency got him arrested and began a period of major uncertainty for the
 band. The rest of the band dabbled with side project Talk Show while he
 sorted himself out and eventually 1999 brought 'No. 4' and a brace of tight
 full tilt rockers mixed with more characteristically melodic material.
 And then Weiland blew it by violating his parole again! Where the band will
 go now is anyone's guess.

 Recommended listening: 'Core'

