@node "STYX"

 STYX

 Widely credited as having invented pomp rock this outfit from Chicago were
 around for over a decade, in one form or another, before achieving any kind
 of notable success. When that success came in the shape of hit single
 'Lady' it signalled the birth of a melodic rock legend. Up to this point
 in the mid 70s the band had been forging a way forward with overblown
 arrangements and a more arty style of rock. With the addition of one
 Tommy Shaw (guitar/vocals) they found the perfect foil to keyboard player
 Denis DeYoung's poppier leanings. Not only that, but Shaw also had a very
 commercial ear when it came to writing and his gradual inclusion in the
 creative process garnered the band their most successful period to date.
 The arrangements were tight and melodic, the vocals were histrionic in
 their intensity - the radio loved them. The likes of 'The Grand Illusion'
 and 'Pieces Of Eight' from the late 70s ensured that Styx would be marked
 as one of the lasting creators of pomp. 1980's 'Cornerstone' gave them
 their first US number one with the super-slick and sugary sweet 'Babe',
 and 1981's 'Paradise Theater' actually went Top Ten in the UK as well!
 This was Styx's most successful period and they would never again match
 it for power and creative focus. Things gradually fractured thereafter
 with various members going off to indulge solo projects and Shaw joining
 @{"Ted Nugent" link "TED NUGENT"} in Damn Yankees. More recently, however, the old creative team
 has come together again for 1998's 'Return To Paradise', a live album
 featuring a handful of new songs penned by both Shaw and DeYoung.

 Recommended listening: 'Pieces Of Eight'

@endnode


@node "SUICIDAL TENDENCIES"

 SUICIDAL TENDENCIES

 The staples of the hardcore sound - big guitars, lots of shouting -
 can be extremely limiting with very few bands actually having the talent,
 or the will to diversify. This noisy bunch, however, appeared to have the
 necessary qualities almost as soon as they started to make a name for
 themselves in around the Venice area of California, back in the very early
 80s. Led by the characteristically bandana-wearing vocalist 'Cyco' Mike
 Muir, his sense of humour was always present throughout the punishing
 noise, even when he was addressing some very serious social and political
 issues. And although their initial releases were somewhat basic, live they
 were an immensely dynamic and powerful unit - in fact, their shows were so
 edgy they were often banned from playing because of the dangers posed by
 out-of-control crowds. This live intensity eventually translated to record
 properly in the mid 80s when the likes of 'Join The Army' (1987) introduced
 elements of thrash metal to their previously trebly hardcore, and as such
 they virtually invented the speed sub-genre of 'skate-punk'. Later albums
 such as 'Lights, Camera ... Revolution' and 'Suicidal For Life' all
 exemplify this gleefully rampant punk hybrid. The band has continued to
 broaden its scope (despite a brief hiatus in the mid 90s), eventually
 bringing elements of funk, and more traditional metal into the mix,
 and latest album 'Freedumb' proves that when it comes to longevity
 and real talent Suicidal are unique entities on the hardcore scene.

 Recommended listening: 'Lights, Camera ... Revolution'

@endnode


@node "SYSTEM OF A DOWN"

 SYSTEM OF A DOWN

 Could Armenia possibly be the least likely place to spawn a metal band of
 the nu persuasion? Stranger things have happened, but as far as musical
 oddities go then this LA-based band are one of the weirdest and most
 compelling of the fresh faces currently upsetting decent-living folk the
 world over. Back in the mid 90s Serj Tankian (vocals), Daron Malakian
 (guitar), Shavo Odadjian (bass) and John Dolmayan (drums) did what any
 fledgling band do: they hawked around a demo tape. The tape finally got
 them a deal, not least because their freakish sound and, frankly, demented
 live shows guaranteed they already had a major following on an underground
 but global scale. When their eponymous debut album was released in 1998 it
 became clear why the buzz about the band was so fervent. The band were,
 quite clearly, proud of their national heritage and the influence of their
 country's music filtered through theirs. Not that this meant dodgy folk
 metal, rather a series of songs that revelled in off-kilter melodies
 and spine-snapping time changes, all finished off with a torrent of
 bile-fuelled, righteous anger. Quite disturbing and quite unique.

 Recommended listening: 'System Of A Down'

