@node "TED NUGENT"

 TED NUGENT

 One of the few guitarists who could actually get away with wearing
 a loincloth on stage - @{"Manowar" link "MANOWAR"} take note! - Ted Nugent is a 110%, red-meat
 eating, guitar-slinging, motor-mouthing nutcase. Famed for his love of
 hunting and complete lack of modesty when it comes to describing his own
 talents, Nugent actually started his career in 60s garage band the Amboy
 Dukes. By the time of the early 70s this had become Ted Nugent And The
 Amboy Dukes before the inevitable happened and he went solo in 1975.
 Vociferously anti-metal, Nugent considers himself a rock 'n' roller and
 when you consider his songwriting talents and accuracy with a rifle you
 can't really argue. The period of his most famous and influential work was
 doubtless the mid to late 70s when his macho posturing and unrestrained axe
 work gave the unsuspecting world the likes of 'Ted Nugent', 'Free For All',
 'Cat Scratch Fever' and the live masterpiece 'Double Live Gonzo'. He was
 lewd, dirty, and most definitely un-PC in just about everything he did.
 Sadly his desire to adopt a more mainstream sound resulted in a distinct
 lack of bite on subsequent releases, and he just seemed to run out of ideas
 as each album began to sound like a pale imitation of its predecessor.
 Fortunately he can still offend with the best of 'em in a live setting and
 his between song raps have lost none of their outrage value.

 Recommended listening: 'Cat Scratch Fever'

@endnode


@node "TESTAMENT"

 TESTAMENT

 Whenever any pioneering wave of creativity crashes through the music scene
 there is always an inevitable second wave - usually the musicians who were
 just old enough to be influenced by their slightly more advanced elders.
 That doesn't mean they're unworthy of attention, merely that they needed
 an initial kick in the right direction. So it was with San Francisco's
 Testament when they formed in the mid 80s after being galvanised into
 action by the path being forged by Exodus, @{"Slayer" link "SLAYER"}, @{"Megadeth" link "MEGADETH"} and @{"Metallica" link "METALLICA"}.
 Called Legacy, when they originally formed, their love of the Metallica
 sound dogged them through their early days, but it is without doubt their
 nave but brutal early period that is remembered with greatest affection.
 Eventually their debut album took their original band name - 1987's
 'The Legacy' - and immediately they found themselves at the forefront of
 the so-called second wave with their speedy and precise attack. Support
 slots with the likes of @{"Anthrax" link "ANTHRAX"} helped cement them into metal fans'
 collective consciousness as one of the heaviest most technically proficient
 units in rock. 1988's 'The New Order' was an equally uncompromising slab of
 focused rage, making much of vocalist Chuck Billy's demented warbling and
 guitarists Alex Skolnick's and Eric Petersons rabid riffing. If anything
 the band became increasingly heavier with subsequent releases but after
 several line-up changes in the 90s their direction seemed a little muddled.
 Nevertheless, 1999 brought a new album in the shape of 'The Gathering'.

 Recommended listening: 'The Legacy'

@endnode


@node "THE BLACK CROWES"

 THE BLACK CROWES

 Since their official inception in 1989, The Black Crowes have proved to be
 one of the most musically uncompromising and adventurous hard rock bands of
 recent years. With 99 per cent of the songs being written by brothers Rich
 (guitar) and Chris (vocals) Robinson, the Crowes' sound harks back to the
 '60 and '70s heyday of hard-rocking blues and bar-room boogie. Deep in the
 mix, you can hear everyone from the Allman Brothers and @{"Lynyrd Skynyrd" link "LYNYRD SKYNYRD"} to
 the Faces - good old-fashioned tales of sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll served
 up with a hefty home-baked slice of southern-flavoured soul. Most recently,
 the band have been touring and recording with Jimmy Page, but their own
 inimitable style is best appreciated on their debut album 'Shake Your
 Money Maker' and the wonderful evocatively titled 'The Southern Harmony
 And Musical Companion' - the latter, incredibly, recorded in a single week.
 And then the band seemed to lose their way somewhat. Their speaking out
 against the corporate sponsorship of rock - famously leading to their
 dismissal from a @{"ZZ Top" link "ZZ TOP"} tour - was one thing, but they began to embrace
 a strangely directionless psychedelic trip with live jams that never seemed
 to end. Happily, this odd detour into self-indulgence was reined in in the
 studio and subsequent albums 'Amorica' and 'Three Snakes And One Charm'
 displayed a band not afraid to stretch and develop their beloved musical
 traditions. Their most recent album, 'By Your Side', has effectively
 banished the spectres of creative excess and is their tightest rocking
 set yet.

 Recommended listening: 'The Southern Harmony And Musical Companion'

@endnode


@node "THE RUNAWAYS"

 THE RUNAWAYS

 Not enough credit is accorded to The Runaways, despite the fact that they
 were the first all-female rock band to achieve any kind of prominence.
 Some might argue that this was down to the cynical manipulations of band
 manager, producer and all-round music entrepreneur Kim Fowley. There is,
 however, a case to be made that Fowley would have got precisely nowhere had
 the girls actually been just talentless bimbos. As it stands The Runaways
 suffered a series of line-up changes over their four years of existence
 (1975-79) but proved to be the launch pad for the careers of both @{"Lita Ford" link "LITA FORD"}
 and Joan Jett, who went on to solo career stardom. As far as the music goes
 The Runaways specialised in hugely energetic slabs of pop metal, liberally
 sprinkled with glitter and glam undertones - the overall aim was to create
 a kind of female @{"Ramones" link "RAMONES"} and the music certainly had the required punky
 attitude and economical style. 1976's self-titled debut contained teen
 anthem 'Cherry Bomb' and was a rough 'n' ready statement of intent ably
 expounded upon by their superb 'Queens Of Noise' (1977). 'Waitin' For The
 Night' merely expanded on the themes of teen rebellion but by now the
 line-up problems were becoming insurmountable and the band split after
 releasing 'And Now ... The Runaways'.

 Recommended listening: 'The Runaways'

@endnode


@node "THE SMASHING PUMPKINS"

 THE SMASHING PUMPKINS

 If any critic of heavy metal tries claiming that the genre is creatively
 bankrupt then they should be directed instantly to the sublime sounds of
 the incomparable The Smashing Pumpkins. Formed back in the late 80s in
 Chicago, by guitarists Billy Corgan and James Iha the band understandably
 fell into the growing grunge scene rather comfortably, what with their
 angsty vocals (courtesy of Corgan) and their heady wall-of-noise riffing.
 Deep within, however, lies a streak of psychedelia which has more in common
 with the rock bands of the 60s and 70s, and a an arty sensibility which has
 little to do with punk. These qualities were evident right from the opening
 strains of 'Gish', an album which brought them almost overnight success.
 It was with their following records that the Pumpkins would really forge
 ahead, however. 'Siamese Dream' was a perfect blend of emotive melody and
 diamond-hard rock, and gave them yet another commercial success. And with
 success comes pointless self-indulgence, or at least it would pointless
 were it not executed with such aplomb. 1995's 'Mellon Collie And The
 Infinite Sadness' was the Pumpkins' 'Physical Graffiti', a sprawling,
 epic, double album which defied expectation with each successive track.
 Inevitably subsequent albums would pale in comparison to 'Mellon Collie'
 and its mad genius excesses. 1998's 'Adore' was a foray into more
 electronic sounds but their most recent 'MACHINA/The Machines OF God'
 appears to have taken the band back to more familiar territory.

 Recommended Listening: 'Mellon Collie And The Infinite Sadness'

@endnode


@node "THIN LIZZY"

 THIN LIZZY

 Up there with the likes of @{"Motorhead" link "MOTORHEAD"} as one of the few groups to truly
 personify the rock 'n' roll ethic, Thin Lizzy wrote it like they lived
 it. Formed originally in Dublin by bassist/vocalist Phil Lynott and school
 friend drummer Brian Downey, they first started out with Alan Bell on
 guitar. For the first few years they suffered general public apathy and
 a number of guitarist line-up changes, but it was with 1976's classic
 'Jailbreak' that Lizzy came of age in style. The band had already earned
 a bad reputation as a hard-living outfit and their most enduring anthem
 to this life style 'The Boys Are Back In Town' was a major hit single.
 More line-up changes followed but a string of classic albums - 'Johnny
 The Fox', 'Bad Reputation', 'Live And Dangerous' and 'Black Rose (A Rock
 Legend)' ensured that the band's place in rock history was guaranteed.
 By now their bad habits were taking a serious toll on the band's stability,
 and particularly on Lynott's failing health. The early 80s records were
 solid enough but it was with the frankly superb 'Thunder And Lightning'
 that the band defied expectation by calling it a day. The split allowed
 Lynott to dry out and continue dabbling with his new solo effort called
 Grand Slam which, incredibly, failed to land a record deal. After a hit
 single collaboration in 1985 with ex-Lizzy guitarist @{"Gary Moore" link "GARY MOORE"} on 'Out
 In The Fields' Lynott tragically died from a drugs overdose. Minus Lynott's
 brilliant songwriting talent and Oirish bonhomie up front the reformed
 Thin Lizzy (featuring various ex-members) are a pale shadow of the band
 in their glory days.

 Recommended listening: 'Live And Dangerous'

@endnode


@node "TOOL"

 TOOL

 The word 'alternative' is probably the best way of describing this totally
 unique outfit from LA. They have deliberately gone out of their way to
 avoid the machinations of both the music industry and also the accepted
 ways of making music. Formed in 1991 by Tool mastermind Maynard James
 Keenan (vocals) and guitarist Adam Jones their sole aim was to create the
 heaviest, most abrasively experimental form of heavy metal they could,
 while at the same time defying everyone's expectations as to exactly where
 they would head to next. When their 1992 'Opiate' EP first emerged it was
 stunningly heavy sonic experience dubbed by some critics as 'hatecore'.
 As a result the band drew comparisons to just about every single-minded
 noise-making outfit from @{"Helmet" link "HELMET"} to the @{"Rollins" link "HENRY ROLLINS"} Band. If 'Opiate' was
 a taster for what Tool were capable of they delivered something even more
 intense with 1993's 'Undertow' album, and with the grungy atmoshere of the
 time there was a ready market for the band's disturbing musings.
 Henry Rollins himself actually made a spoken word appearance on 'Bottom'
 and tracks like 'Prison Sex' - their comment on child abuse - made for
 particularly bleak, but fascinating, listening. Already the bands
 experimental attitude had garnered huge amounts of both critical and fan
 praise, but it took three years to come up with 'Aenima' and when they
 did the band baffled everyone. Heavy on atmosphere, parts of 'Aenima'
 came dangerously close to prog rock in places - an extraordinary feat,
 considering the band were still bomb heavy too. This unwillingness to
 pander to people's expectations has led them to turn down lucrative
 support slots and TV appearances, to basically defy the rules by which
 bands progress through the music industry. Maynard James Keenan's latest
 twisted career move has been to create another band A Perfect Circle,
 leaving fans of Tools particularly dark brand of arty rock wondering just
 what will happen next.

 Recommended listening: 'Undertow'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

