@node "TYPE O NEGATIVE"

 TYPE O NEGATIVE

 The doomy, gloomy Type O Negative might seem to be a million miles from
 the hardcore scene of the 80s and yet it was from the remnants of notorious
 New York band Carnivore that bassist/vocalist Pete Steele created this
 miserable outfit. Steele, however, would soon prove to be well beyond the
 two-dimensional thrashing of New York hardcore. He would also prove to be
 something of an enigma when it came to the lyrical subject matter of his
 new band. With 1991's 'Slow, Deep And Hard' debut, the music was slowed
 right down to a dirge-like quality made all the more grinding and powerful
 through some painfully distorted guitar noise. And then there were the
 actual songs which brought all kinds of accusations about misogyny and
 misanthropy. One thing was for sure, Steele's dry and dour sense of humour
 informed pretty much everything the band did. With 1993's 'Bloody Kisses'
 Steele introduced more Beatles-y style melodies to counterpoint his rich
 resonant vocals and depressing lyrics, although it was still hard to tell
 if throughout his tales of misery he wasn't really just playing a massive
 joke on everyone. In equal turns funny and downright serious, by now the
 band were making serious commercial headway and with 1996's gothic
 masterpiece 'October Rust' they began building upon their unlikely pop
 appeal. Steele even went so far as to pose nude in Playgirl magazine.
 1999's 'World Coming Down' merely enhanced the band's reputation as highly
 enjoyable world-class miserablists with a suspect sense of humour.

 Recommended listening: 'October Rust'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Bloody Kisses'

