@node "UFO"

 UFO

 One of the finest hard rock bands Britain ever produced UFO have influenced
 countless newcomers with their tough and melodic brand of hard rock. Formed
 way back in 1969 the early incarnation of the band was nothing like the
 tight outfit that went on to greatness during the 70s. Their first three
 albums were highly dubious affairs very influenced by the droning
 psychedelia of space rock. It was when they were supported in Germany,
 in 1973, by the @{"Scorpions" link "SCORPIONS"} that UFO finally took off, so to speak. Their
 guitarist @{"Michael Schenker" link "MICHAEL SCHENKER"} helped them out when guitarist Bernie Marsden
 failed to show up for a gig and ended up joining the band.
 Employing Schenker was the smartest move the could have made because his
 firey, passionate style led to a brilliant clutch of albums. Records like
 'Force It', 'Lights Out', and 'Obsession' were packed with punchy, powerful
 rock songs and some superlative guitar work from Schenker. A fine example
 of the band's storming live performances can also be sampled on the
 double-live 'Strangers In The Night'. This period of major commercial
 success, naturally had it's downside - in this case, the band found it
 hard not to live the rock 'n' roll life style to the max. The result was
 an chemical and alcohol intake of stunning proportions and eventual
 implosion. Schenker left, and while the likes of 'No Place To Run',
 'The Wild The Willing And The Innocent', and 'Mechanix' saw the band into
 the early 80s they never achieved those halcyon heights ever again.
 Eventually things just fizzled out in 1983. There have been subsequent
 efforts over the intervening years, most notably by singer Phil Mogg,
 to get UFO flying again, and a new album featuring Schenker appears to
 be in the pipeline at present.

 Recommended listening: 'Force It'

@endnode


