 URIAH HEEP

 When Uriah Heep formed in 1968 they had it all, the blues-heavy sound,
 the songs about sword and sorcery, the Roger Dean fantasy cover art.
 The embraced so many rock cliches it was frightening but at the same time,
 despite their lack of irony and genre excesses, the Heep did epitomise
 a certain style of rock, a style that still enjoys many adherents today.
 When they first started rehearsals in 1969, by sheer chance, they found
 themselves next door to @{"Deep Purple" link "DEEP PURPLE"} who were developing their own brand
 of bluesy hard rock. When Heep's debut 'Very 'Eavy, Very 'Umble' was
 released in 1970 some of the Purple influence seems to have rubbed off
 on them. And while Purple's Hammond-dominated sound was very much their
 own, so Heep's identity was unique enough to influence upcoming outfits
 such as Golden Earring and early @{"Scorpions" link "SCORPIONS"}. The band managed to make
 a name for themselves basically by having a couple of truly knock-out
 cuts each album and fans loved the likes of Gypsy (from their debut),
 'Bird Of Prey' (from 'Salisbury') and 'July Morning (from 'Look At
 Yourself'). The songs 'Easy Livin'' and 'Sweet Lorraine' made their two
 1972 albums 'Demons And Wizards' and 'The Magician's Birthday' even more
 successful. Sadly, with punk in the late 70s Heep, as with so many of
 their contemporaries, began to stagnate. That and the thrash movement
 would have killed any less determined outfit. Heep, however, obviously
 don't have the desire to die gracefully and have managed to soldier on
 well into the 90s. Their last album was 1998's 'Sonic Origami'.

 Recommended listening: 'Very 'Eavy, Very 'Umble'

