@node "VOIVOD"

 VOIVOD

 Modern bands such as @{"Fear Factory" link "FEAR FACTORY"} might think they have a monopoly on all
 things cyber but this bunch of Canadian techno-junkies - techno as in
 technology, not dance - had long since cornered that particular market.
 Formed back in 1982, Eric Forrest (bass/vocals), Dennis D'Amour (guitar)
 and Michel Langevin (drums), were very far from being progenitors of
 industrial metal despite their name and conceptual stance. In fact, they
 were more punk than anything else, a musical style which seemed at odds
 with their love of sci-fi. During the 80s this love of the fantastical had
 the band leaping off in pursuit of the bizarre and epic tale of Voivod in
 tandem with a dischordant musical style which drew them into the thrash
 scene on the backs of such wonderfully titled albums as 'War And Pain'
 and 'RRROOOAAARRR!'. Their output was self-consciously obnoxious when they
 first began - witness the latter album's unequivocally titled 'Fuck Off
 And Die' track - a style which gradually became less overtly offensive
 and became simply strange with such later albums as 'Nothingface' and
 'Angel Rat'. Most recently the band have been critically lauded for the
 experimentation of 1995's 'Negatron', and their latest album, 'Phobos',
