@node "WASP"

 WASP

 We Are Sexual Perverts or White Angle Saxon Protestants? Judging by WASPs
 outrageous output at the peak then the former really fits, much, much
 better. Like a leather glove over a fist of steel, in fact. Created by
 ex-New York Doll Blackie Lawless in 1982 WASP's raison d'etre was to shock,
 provoke and outrage - laudable aims one and all, aims which they achieved
 seemingly without trying. Their stage show involved 'torturing' a woman
 on a rack, chucking loads of raw meat and blood around, and, of course,
 there was Blackie's infamous flame-throwing cod piece. Already legends
 on the live circuit around Los Angeles, their tasteless rock circus wasn't
 confined simply to their cod theatrics. They famously signed to major label
 Capitol and then tried to get them to release the unassuming 'Animal
 (Fuck Like A Beast)' as a single! That song would make them, quite rightly,
 stars of the 80s metal scene. The cartoonish brand of schlock horror made
 them prime targets for parents groups like the PMRC and they rose to the
 challenge like true gladiators. 'WASP' was a magnificent debut, but
 subsequent albums 'Last Command' and 'Inside the Electric Circus' proved
 that at heart they were fine commercial songwriters with a keen ear for
 chart gold. The band's late 80s output was no less impressive, but a shift
 away from overt shock rock and a greater desire to explore their potential
 resulted in the more commercial 'The Headless Children'. Meanwhile 1992
 actually found them dabbling with (gasp!) a concept album, the rather
 strange 'Crimson Idol'. More recently they appear to have reverted back
 to type with the gross-out charm of 'Helldorado'.

 Recommended listening: 'WASP'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: 'Inside the Electric Circus'

@endnode


@node "WHITESNAKE"

 WHITESNAKE

 Of all the most successful British rock bands of recent Whitesnake must
 still rate as one of the most influential and thoroughly entertaining.
 They officially came into existence in 1978 with the four-track 'Snakebite'
 EP (actually under the name David Coverdale's Whitesnake), and basically
 provided a vehicle for former @{"Deep Purple" link "DEEP PURPLE"} vocalist David Coverdale to
 exercise his chest-beatingly macho style of bluesy hard rock. At this they
 were quite marvellous, featuring in their ranks such solid rock talent as
 guitarists Bernie Marsden and Micky Moody, bassist Neil Murray, drummer
 David Dowle and keyboardist Pete Solley. The latter was soon replaced by
 Purple's Jon Lord. The band went on to turn out some stunningly powerful
 albums of thrusting hard rock, in particular, 'Lovehunter' (and its
 absurdly sexist sleeve art) and the even less subtle 'Slide It In'.
 However, it was with a certain little album, unassumingly titled '1987',
 that Coverdale's fortunes would soar. The earlier classic blues sound
 had been polished to a commercial gleam and the overall feel was one of
 all-conquering majesty. The band had been re-invented as a major
 stadium-filler for the big-haired 80s. The hits flowed, not least the
 awesome 'Still Of The Night', and the band enjoyed sell out tours
 especially in the US. Unfortunately, a certain creative short-sightedness
 crept in thereafter and 1989's 'Slip Of The Tongue', devoid of the hoary
 old charm of previous outings was an impressive album for all the wrong
 reasons. The songs were solid enough but the technical prowess of guitarist
 @{"Steve Vai" link "STEVE VAI"} was ill-suited to the Whitesnake style. Since then Coverdale has been
 relatively quiet save for a project involving Jimmy Page (@{"Led Zeppelin" link "LED ZEPPELIN"})
 and a rather muted 'Snake outing in 1997.

 Recommended listening: '1987'

@endnode


@node "WHITE ZOMBIE"

 WHITE ZOMBIE

 Formed at the height of the thrash explosion in 1985, White Zombie were
 at first a fairly generic metal outfit combining battering rhythms with
 frenetic guitar work in a style that differed very little from their
 contemporaries. At the roots of the Zombie sound, however, was the
 demented genius of one Rob Zombie, for whom being yet another death-metal
 style band was simply not enough. Rob Zombie's love of trash culture and,
 in particular, EC horror comics and sub-standard b-grade shock flicks
 provided him with plenty of lyrical avenues to explore in the way of
 schlocky gore and tongue-in-cheek humour. Their first album, 1988's
 'Soul Crusher' featured such joyously titled tales of malevolence and
 perversity as 'Shack Of Hate' and 'Die Zombie Die'. Follow-up, 1989's
 'Make Them Die Slowly' was more of the same although their bass-heavy
 style of grinding metal was heading away from thrash and more towards
 a sort of bouncing groove. A move to Geffen in the early 90s, however,
 provided the funds and time to fully realise Rob Zombie's dastardly
 scheme for world domination. 'La Sexorcisto: Devil Music Volume I' was
 a rib-crunching beast of a record, all shock horror and sense-swamping
 noise - it was classic sci-fi and comics brought to life. As if to
 underline the fact that White Zombie existed to fulfill Rob Zombie's own
 creative agenda 1995's ludicrously titled 'Astrocreep 2000: Songs Of Love
 Destruction, And Other Synthetic Delusions Of The Electric Head' found
 the man positively revelling in his own Technicolor swamp of sound and
 aural fury, with live shows that attempted to bring the dazzling spectacle
 to life. Since then White Zombie have parted ways and Rob Zombie continues
 his adventures in hi-fi as a solo artist.

 Recommended listening: 'Astrocreep 2000: Songs Of Love Destruction,
                         And Other Synthetic Delusions Of The Electric Head'

 ZUBi's recommended listening: AGREE

