 YNGWIE MALMSTEEN

 Technically enormously talented Yngwie Malmsteen is without doubt
 a guitarist's guitarist - his finger-flinging exploits are known the
 world over not just for the furious speed but their extreme precision.
 As a classical music fan from an early age the young Malmsteen was
 naturally drawn to the baroque stylings of @{"Deep Purple" link "DEEP PURPLE"}'s Ritchie Blackmore.
 Modelling himself on Blackmore he played in a number of bands in his native
 Sweden before impressing LA guitar fan Mike Varney (head of the Shrapnel
 record label) who had Malmsteen join forces with vocalist Ron Keel in
 Steeler. This partnership was shortlived but allowed Malmsteen to immerse
 himself in the LA music scene and so launch a solo career. His new band
 was called Rising Force and it was a blustering heavy metal outfit par
 excellence. No technical extremes were too tough to reach and their 1984
 debut was an unbeatable testament to a man at the peak of his powers.
 Sure, his and the band's style owed much to Ritchie Blackmore and @{"Rainbow" link "RAINBOW"}
 but it was outstandingly, endearingly over-the-top all the same and
 influenced thousands of equally passionate guitarists over the years.
 The remainder of the 80s brought a constantly fracturing line-up and
 several lacklustre albums but the 90s brought various dabblings with
 classical and orchestral styles, plus the added bonus of a burgeoning
 career in Japan.

 Recommended listening: 'Rising Force'

