 ZZ TOP

 Starting out with the unlikely name of the Moving Sidewalks these
 notoriously hairy Sons Of The South - Houston, Texas, to be precise - were
 a phenomenon in their home state long before they shot to international
 acclaim in the 80s. With their dirty, grinding blues sound guitarist
 Billy Gibbons, bassist Dusty Hill and drummer Frank Beard were filling
 stadiums way back in the 70s with such classic albums as 'Tres Hombres',
 'Fandango', 'Tejas' and 'Deguello', every one of them an authentic and
 potent brew of southern boogie and knowing tongue-in-cheek humour.
 It wasn't until the advent of MTV, however, that they found a truly
 international audience as the tried-and-tested girls 'n' cars formula
 catapulted the synth-laden boogie of 'Eliminator' to the top of the charts
 with MTV hits like 'Legs', 'TV Dinners' and 'Sharp Dressed Man'. Things
 continued to go stratospheric with 1985's 'Afterburner' but have appeared
 to dip more recently as the band have tamed their original gritty sound
 increasingly for radio and MTV consumption. Nevertheless, when it comes
 to the perfect accompaniment to an ice cold brew on a steamy summer night
 then these good ol' boys are damn hard to beat.

 Recommended listening: 'Tres Hombres'

